@node SlideSorter "Slide Sorter screen"
 The Slide Sorter screen is the heart of Presentation Master.  The
 "Navel of the Universe" if you will.  From here the user can view
 his entire presentation and do overall manipulation, such as slide
 arranging, the placing of narration and speaker notes on individual
 slides, the specification of slideshow attributes such as transition
 and duration, and the creation of new slides.  Also the user can load
 multiple presentations and move slides or groups of slides between
 the different shows.

        @{" Main Slide Rack " link SlideRack   }       @{" Transitions     " link Transitions}
        @{" New Slides      " link NewSlides   }       @{" Settings        " link Termination}
        @{" TrashCan        " link TrashCan    }       @{" Hot Spots       " link HotSpots}
        @{" ClipBoard       " link ClipBoard   }       @{" SlideShow       " link SlideShow}
        @{" CurrentSlide    " link CurrentSlide}       @{" Shortcuts       " link SlideSorterShortcuts}
        @{" Speaker Notes   " link SpeakerNotes}
@endnode

@node SlideSorterShortcuts "Slide Sorter screen Keyboard Shortcuts"
 There are a number of keyboard shortcuts that apply to actions on
 the slide sorter screen:
   CTRL-LeftAmiga-click on a clipboard slide or a child slide will
      trash that slide.  This is a shortcut for dragging the slide
      to the trashcan.
   CTRL-Alt-click on a child slide or the parent slide (when at the
      very top of the show) to put it into the clipboard.  If the
      Shift key is ALSO held down, then it clones the slide/show into
      the clipboard.  If the click is on the clipboard, then the top
      slide will be copied/swapped to the main show (if the main
      show is at the topmost slide).
   Shift-click or Shift-grab-drag-drop will duplicate a slide, and
      all its progenitors.
   CTRL-drag of a slide in the clipboard to the trashcan will trash
      ALL slides currently in the clipboard.  Note that ALL of these
      slides will be held in the trashcan for retrieval so if they
      are retrieved and put into the slide rack, then ALL the slides
      will be siblings in the slide rack.
   Shift-Help will toggle the trashcan image with a black-hole image.

 A way to help remember some shortcuts is to visualize the CTRL key as
 the slide you are clicking on, and the Alt key as the clipboard and
 the Left Amiga key as the trashcan.  Then holding the CTRL key along
 with the Amiga or Alt key will cause the clicked slide to go to the
 indicated location.
@endnode

@node SlideRack "Main Slide Rack"
 A slideshow is maintained as a heirarchical tree of slides, much as
 in an outline.  Unlike an outline, however, the structure can include
 text, graphics, images, and animations.  This structure is graphically
 shown with @{" thumbnails " link G_Thumbnail} of slides.  The show can be edited easily,
 moving entire substructures or individual slides with the same speed.

 A slideshow consists of a master slide at the top with as many
 "child" slides as desired below it.  Indeed, the slide sorter screen
 displays such a "parent" and its rack of "children" slides graphically
 with @{" thumbnails " link G_Thumbnail}.  In turn, each of the child slides can also have
 child slides, ad infinitum.  This tree-like structure has many benefits
 and contributes to the power of presentation created in Presentation
 Master.

 One may add new Empty slides by either clicking on the stack of empty
 slides to the left side of the screen, or "grabing" one empty slide off
 that stack and dragging it to the desired location in the rack of child
 slides.  Clicking on the up and down pointing buttons next to the parent
 and child slides will move up and down the heirarchy so one can work at
 any level desired.
@endnode

@node NewSlides
 Click on the stack of New Slides to add a new Empty slide to the slide
 rack.  If desired, grab a slide from the New Slides stack and drag it
 to the desired position in the rack.
@endnode

@node TrashCan
 The Trashcan in the lower right corner of the screen is used for
 discarding single slides or whole branches of slides.  Simply grab a
 slide and drag it to the trashcan.  The last item dropped in the
 trashcan can be retrieved if desired.  This is intended as an undo
 feature, in case you suddenly realize you didn't really want to trash
 that slide.

 WARNING!! Do not count on a slide remaining in the trashcan
 for any period of time.  It may be discarded automatically at any time
 by Presentation Master should more memory be needed (or for a variety
 of other reasons).

 A @{" shortcut " link SlideSorterShortcuts} is to hold the CTRL+Amiga key down and click on any slide
 in the rack, or the top parent slide of the current show, or a slide
 in the clipboard, and the slide (plus its descendents) will be quickly
 trashed to the trashcan.

 A way to help remember this shortcut is to visualize the CTRL key as
 the slide you are clicking on, and the Alt key as the clipboard and
 the Left Amiga key as the trashcan.  Then holding the CTRL key along
 with the Amiga or Alt key will cause the clicked slide to go to the
 indicated location (if it is appropriate).
@endnode

@node ClipBoard
 The clipboard (not to be confused with the Amiga Clipboard) is provided as
 a holding area for slides. You can load from disk direct to the clipboard,
 or save any item in the clipboard to disk.  Slides can be dragged between
 the clipboard, the trashcan, and the main slide rack at will.  Each slide
 in the clipboard can be either a single slide, or may have many child
 slides and further children so each slide can be a complete "branch" of
 slides, or, indeed, a complete presentation.  If you drag a slide from
 the clipboard to the top parent slide on the screen, then whatever was
 previously in the show position will be automatically placed in the
 clipboard, so it becomes a "swap".  You can see the top slide via its
 @{" thumbnail " link G_Thumbnail}, but as many slides as desired, and for which you have memory,
 can be placed into the clipboard.  The up/down buttons scroll through
 the main slides placed in the clipboard, but not their child slides.
 To see child slides to a slide you must move it to the main rack first,
 however red arrows to the right of the slide name indicates that
 child slides exist.

 A @{" shortcut " link SlideSorterShortcuts} here is to hold the CTRL+Alt keys down together and click
 on a slide in the clipboard.  It will be swapped with the main show.
 If you clicked on a slide in the slide rack, or the top parent slide
 of the current show, then it will be placed in the clipboard.

 Another shortcut is to hold the CTRL+Amiga keys down together and click
 on a slide in the clipboard.  The slide will be trashed to the trashcan.

 A way to help remember these shortcuts is to visualize the CTRL key as
 the slide you are clicking on, and the Left Alt key as the clipboard and
 the Left Amiga key as the trashcan.  Then holding the CTRL key along
 with the Amiga or Alt key will cause the clicked slide to go to the
 indicated location (if it is appropriate).
@endnode

@node CurrentSlide
 Whatever slide is currently highlighted in the rack (or the parent) will
 also appear in the Current Slide position in the lower left of the screen.
 The buttons within the rectangular region on the slide sorter screen
 labeled "Edit Current Slide" all apply to that slide.

 This includes:
    @{" Speaker Notes " link SpeakerNotes}
    @{" Transitions   " link Transitions}
    @{" Settings      " link Termination}
    @{" HotSpot       " link HotSpots}
    @{" Play button   " link SlideShow} (the one with the arrow on it)
     Show button (with two vertical lines on it) - this simply displays
         the slide full-screen.

 Clicking on the slide @{" thumbnail " link G_Thumbnail} will cause Presentation Master to
 go to the slide editing or creation function for that slide.  If
 the slide is an Empty slide, then you will be prompted for the
 @{" Slide Type " link SlideTypes} you wish to create.
@endnode

@node Transitions
 Transitions for slideshow module.  There are several basic types of
 transitions provided:

   Cut    - An instantaneous flip from one slide to another.
   Fade   - Fades old slide out to black and then fades the new one in.
   Zoom   - This displays an expanding rectangle from a hotspot out to full
            screen, at which point the new picture appears.  On leaving the
            slide and returning to the hotspot, the rectangle appears and
            contracts to the hotspot.  While it is intended for hotspot
            usage, it can be used at any point.
   Wipes  - These perform a wipe in the indicated direction from one
            picture to the next.  The two pictures MUST be the same size
            and if the color palettes are different, the palette will be
            gradually changed from the old to the new.
   Block  - This is like a wipe except the new picture appears in 144
            blocks on the screen (a 12x12 grid).  The pictures MUST be
            of the same size, and the palette will be gradually changed
            from old to new.
   Scrolls- These are some of the most effective transitions.  They utilize
            multiple viewports on the Amiga to do vertical wipes, scrolls,
            covers, and reveals.  The two pictures do NOT have to be the
            same size or mode.  You can transition smoothly between a lores
            HAM picture and a hires picture with overscan.  Each portion
            of the screen, at any instant, is the correct resolution AND
            color palette!
@endnode

@node Termination "Slide Show Settings Help"
 This window provides full control over timing of slides in an on-screen
 @{" SlideShow " link SlideShow}.  Also it provides control over @{" narration " link Narration}.
@endnode

@node SpeakerNotes
 Speaker Notes can be appended to any slide.  They are used in only one
 place - on the speaker notes output to a @{" PostScript " link PostScript} device.  This places
 a reduced size slide on the top of a portrait page, and the speaker
 notes on the bottom.
@endnode

@node HotSpots
 For manual play of slides in an on-screen @{" SlideShow " link SlideShow}, Presentation Master
 allows you to specify rectangular "Hot Spots" on a parent slide which are
 bound to child slides.  During the show, one can click on one of these to
 invoke the child slide.  This is like, in the "old days", one having a
 stack of overhead charts where there were many extra charts to provide
 support of certain areas if questions came up.  Here, if someone asks
 about some subject on a slide, one can simply click on that area to bring
 up a more detailed chart of the subject.

 Creation of hotspots is easy.  First, the parent MUST be optioned (on the
 Settings window) for both manual play and for HotSpot invocation of child
 slides.  Next, in the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter}, select the child slide and click on
 the HotSpot button.  The parent slide will be drawn, wherupon you drag
 a rectangle with the mouse to indicate the hotspot location.  Upon
 releasing the rectangle, control returns to the slide sorter screen
 and you are done.

 In play, HotSpots respond in a similar fashion to Amiga buttons.  When you
 place the cursor over the spot and press the left mouse button, the Hot
 Spot will complement.  If you then release the mouse button it will be
 selected.  If you move the cursor off the Hot Spot and then release the
 mouse button, the action is canceled.

 The difference between Visible and Invisible hotspots is that Visible
 hotspots will make their presence known when the mouse cursor is over
 them by displaying a marquee (rectangle of moving dashes) around the
 hotspot.  The invisible one does nothing special until you click on it.
 It is up to you to provide any graphics, such as a button, where the
 gotspot is located.
@endnode

@node SlideShow
 The Play button below the CurrentSlide and below the ClipBoard will invoke
 the current SlideShow module.  At present only one SlideShow module is
 provided with Presentation Master.  However, it is expected that
 additional modules will be made available which have differing features
 such as support for some of the alternate graphics boards available for
 the Amiga.
@endnode

@node SlideTypes
 A slide can be any one of four types:

  @{" Empty Slides   " link G_EmptySlide}
  @{" IFF Slides     " link G_ImageSlide}
  @{" Black Slides   " link G_BlackSlide}
  @{" Layered Slides " link LayeredSlide}

 From the menu in the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen, you can change the type of
 any slide.  However, if you change a layered slide to something else,
 you will lose any data placed on that slide.

 Upon creating a new slide (starting with an Empty Slide) you will be
 asked which of the other three types of slide you wish to create.  If
 you wish a layered slide, you may first select the template desired
 from the popup gadget.
@endnode

@node LayeredSlide "Layered Slides"
 Layered Slides

    These are the real core of Presentation Master.  These are the slides
    which are normally created within the program and here is where
    Presentation Master really shines.

    A layered slide is made up of at least two, and normally more, layers.
    At the bottom is the background layer which consists of the graphical
    design of the slide and its @{" backdrop " link Backdrops} image.  The background is
    normally pre-designed by the @{" Template " link Templates}.  At the top is the
    annotation paint layer which is a full screen object-based paint layer
    so one may add annotation graphics over the top of any layered slide.

    In between are as many layers as desired which are normally not full
    screen size.  These consist of four types as follows:

     Title Layers
         These are identical to @{" text layers " link TextLayer} below except there is a link
         between the text in this layer and the name of the slide back on
         the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.
    @{" Text Layers " link TextLayer}
         This layer utilizes a mini-word-processor for the entry or import
         of text and its display in indented and/or bulleted fashion.
    @{" Graphics Layers " link Drawing}
         This layer utilizes an object based paint package for drawing any
         type of graphic you wish.  You can also import @{" EPS " link G_EPS} graphic
         images or @{" clipart " link ClipArt} or utilize one of may provided modules for
         the creation of complex objects such as bar charts, pie
         charts, outline text, etc.  Any object, once drawn, created,
         or imported, can be edited and even distorted, bent, or
         fit to a circle.
    @{" Image Layers " link ImageLayer}
         This layer permits the import of any @{" IFF " link G_IFF} picture or brush into a
         rectangular region on the slide.  While it will have to be mapped
         onto the pixels of the screen, and have its colors remapped to the
         slide color palette, the full resolution and colors of the
         original image will be retained for future output to @{" PostScript " link PostScript}
         devices.

    Annotation paint and Background paint layers utilize the same object-
    based paint system as used in graphics layers.
@endnode

@node Narration
 You can utilize the Amiga narration device to add voice narration to
 an on-screen slideshow.  This can be done, slide-by-slide, in either
 of two ways:
   1) You can specify text to be read by the narrator, by going to the
      narration text entry window via the settings window on the slide
      sorter screen.  Then this text is the text to be read.  Be sure
      to turn on narration for that slide in the same settings window.
   2) If narration is turned on, but there is no specific narration
      text provided, then the slideshow module will read the text from
      any text and/or title layers (paint layers and non-layered slides
      have nothing to narrate).  N.B. that if you @{" vulcanize " link G_Vulcanize} your show,
      then the slide is turned into an IFF slide, and so this option
      will NOT work.  For a vulcanized show, and for any IFF or black
      slides in any show, you can only utilize method #1 above.
 One can, in addition, control the speech characteristics via the
 narration control window which is reached via the slideshow menu item
 in the project menu in the slide sorter screen.
@endnode

@node ClipArt
 Presentation Master can import clipart which is in Adobe Illustrator
 @{" EPS " link G_EPS} format.  There are @{" samples of ClipArt " link ClipArtSamples} provided
 with Presentation Master for you to see how they work and how they
 might fit into your work.  If you find them useful, you might consider
 purchasing more.

 Importing ClipArt is done from any graphics layer by selecting the
 "Import EPS" creation module from the Create/Other menu in paint.
 Most of the commercial EPS clipart (primarily on the PC and
 Macintosh platforms) is in Illustrator format.  Some of this is
 available from Oxxi and other publishers on Amiga format media.
 However, most PC clipart can be utilized directly by installing
 the @{" CrossDOS " link CrossDOS} utility, in which case you can directly read PC 720K
 3-1/2 inch floppies.  Be sure, if you purchase any PC clipart, that
 it is in Illustrator format and it is on this format floppy, AND that
 it is NOT in compressed format.  Otherwise you may have to have
 access to a PC to decompress and/or transfer it to a 720K floppy.
 If a product is compressed then you may be able to decompress it on
 your Amiga.  Lharc is provided with Presentation Master (it is used
 during installation) and will decompress most .lzh and .arc files
 found on PC diskettes.  Pkazip is available on bulletin boards and on
 public domain disk libraries and will decompress most .zip files from
 the PC.  However, there are other compression formats on the PC which
 will require an actual PC compatible computer for decompression.

 If the EPS files are in PC EPS format (commonly referred to as @{" EPSF " link G_EPSF}
 format) including a @{" TIFF " link G_TIFF} preview image, then the @{" file requester " link FileReq} can
 produce the preview image very quickly (by clicking on the @{" Preview " link FR_Preview}
 button) so you can see what the image looks like prior to actually
 importing it.

 When this clipart is imported, it is converted internally to paint
 objects in the object based paint system of Presentation Master.  This
 means you are free to edit it in any way you would normally edit any
 other paint object - bend it, distort it, etc.  This process is quite
 complete in its duplication of the original artwork.  However, be
 aware of the fact that it is not completely compatible.  The areas
 of incompatibility are in the area of transformation matrices and
 some other capabilities which are not supported in Presentation Master.
 One area you might run into is the fact that text is not always
 handled properly.  In particular rotated and rescaled text will not
 be properly transformed.  Perhaps in a future version of Presentation
 Master this will be rectified.  In the meantime, if text isn't properly
 converted, you may have to hand-edit it to make it render correctly
 (or eliminate the text entirely).  If you have any questions, call
 Oxxi for more details.

 You can also export paint objects as EPS files, complete with a preview
 image, using the @{" Export_EPS " link ExportEPS} module.  This module is not included with
 the Presentation Master product, but will be made available on an
 expansion pak at a later date.
@endnode

@node Templates
 All layered slides are created using a template as a basic starting
 format.  Templates relieve the user from the drudgery of having to
 re-design all the basic stuff which is common from slide to slide.
 In addition, templates enforce a uniform appearance to all the slides
 of a presentation.  The user can utilize any of the 16 or more template
 families provided with Presentation Master, or he can alter them to
 suit his own taste, or he can create completely new templates of his
 liking.

 Templates are organized into Families of templates.  Each family shares a
 common appearance, although each template in the family has different
 basic features.  One may be oriented to text entry, while another may be
 oriented to graphics.  The 16 standard template families provided each
 have 7 templates in them as follows:
    Text1        - A simple text slide template
    Title1       - A simple title slide which uses the base slide name for
                   the title.  This is a very fast and easy way to provide
                   a title slide for a show.
    Title2       - Like Title 1 except a paint layer is provided so one can
                   utilize graphics and, in particular, outline text for
                   more dramatic titles.
    Chart1       - Similar to Text1 in layout, except it has a graphics
                   layer instead of text.
    Chart/Text1  - Similar to Text1 except it has both a text and a
                   graphics layer, with the graphics layer on top and the
                   text layer below it.
    Chart/Text1x - Similar to Text1 except it has both a text and a
                   graphics layer, with the graphics layer to the left
                   and the text layer to the right.
    Paint Only   - This is a blank slide with no layers except the
                   backdrop and the annotation paint layer.  This is used
                   for basic paint operations where one wants a plain
                   slide with only the paint objects on it.  There is no
                   title layer here.

 The Altering or Creating of templates is very simple.  There are two ways
 to go about it.  The first is provided on the @{" template panels " link TemplatePanel} invoked from
 a single slide or from the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.  Here you can change the
 @{" color palette " link ColorPalette}  of a template.  In the template panel from the slide
 sorter screen, you can also change the @{" backdrop " link Backdrops}  and the @{" page size " link PageSize} as
 well as being able to save the template back out with the same or
 different name.

 The second way is to simply load the template family as a show.  Once in
 the show rack it is obvious how the various templates are organized.  They
 are simply a rack of child slides under a parent which is an Empty slide
 and is ignored when used as a template family.  The name on the parent is
 the name of the family, and the names of the child slides correspond to
 the names listed above (Text1, ...).

 The names of each template are important if you ever wish to do global
 changing of the template on an entire show to a new template family.
 These names are how the program knows which template in a new family to
 apply to each slide of the show.  If you never expect to do global
 changes of the template, then the name is of little consequence except
 it is how the template is identified in the popup menu.
@endnode

@node Backdrops
 This refers to the way the screen is initialized prior to carrying
 out any background paint operations.  The backdrop upon which a
 slide is built can be created in one of three basic ways:

 Solid Fill
   In any of the 16 basic palette colors.

 Gradations
   Horizontal or Vertical gradations, either double or single, can be
   specified using any two colors from the 16 basic palette colors.  A
   double gradation has the first color at the center of the screen, and
   the second color at the left and right for a horizontal gradation, or
   on the top and bottom for a vertical.  A single gradation has the first
   color at the top or left and the second at the bottom or right.

 IFF Backdrops
   At least 45 backdrop @{" IFF " link G_IFF} files are provided with Presentation Master,
   and the user can add to these with ease.  Any IFF file which is not as
   large as the screen will be centered and tiled outward (except for
   using a std NTSC size picture on a std PAL screen).  In this way,
   repeating patterns can be created as small brushes rather than having
   to have full screen pictures.  It is to the users benefit to have any
   new IFF backdrop file conform to a few simple rules set out in the
   manual.  However, any 16 color, or less, picture or brush can be used,
   including the nice backdrops provided with competitive products.
   If you are running on a @{" PAL " link G_PAL} machine, then any backdrop image of exactly
   the @{" NTSC " link G_NTSC} dimensions (640x400) will be stretched to fit the PAL screen
   (640x512).  In this way, the std backdrop images supplied will be full
   screen on a PAL machine.
@endnode

@node PageSize
 The pagesize panel permits you to specify such things as page
 orientation (landscape/portrait) and the size, both on the screen
 in pixels, and also in user space (inches, cm., @{" points " link G_Point}, etc.).

 The size on the screen is limited at present to the actual
 screen size (640x400 in NTSC, and 640x512 in PAL).  If specified
 smaller than the screen then one can visually see the size via a
 border drawn on the screen, although at times the border may
 not show up.

 The combination of screen size and user-space dimensions will
 be used for aspect ratio for drawing things like circles and
 squares, and for importing @{" EPS " link G_EPS} @" clipart " link ClipArt}.
@endnode

@node TemplatePanel "Help for Slide Sorter Template Panel"
 This is the template panel which is invoked from the project
 menu on the slide @{" sorter screen " link SlideSorter}.  This panel controls global
 operations on and with the templates.  (There is a similar @{" panel " link GetTemplatePanell}
 accessed from the menu in any slide layer).

 Here you can load a new @{" template family " link Templates} from disk and even
 change its overall color scheme, its @{" backdrop " link BackDrops}, and/or its
 @{" pagesize " link PageSize}.  Upon any changes you can then save the revised
 template family back to disk.

 You can also load a new family, or revise the current one,
 and then globally set all layered slides to the new template
 family.  In doing this, Presentation Master will attempt
 to match templates in the new family with the actual template
 currently on each slide.  It will notify you if it cannot
 do so.  If there are active layers present on the old slide
 for which there is no corresponding layer on the new
 template, then the old layer will be carried forward into
 the new template on the slide.
@endnode

@node GetTemplatePanel "Help for single slide Template Panel"
 This is the template panel which is invoked from the project
 menu from within any layer of a particular slide.  Its intent
 is to be able to change the @{" template " link Templates} on the current slide
 without having to return to the slide sorter screen.  There
 is a similar @{" panel " link TemplatePanel} invoked from the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.

 Here you can select the desired template from the current
 template family, using the popup menu, and, upon clicking
 "OK", it will be inserted into the current slide.

 You can also load a new template family from disk and/or
 change the color scheme of the currently loaded family.
 However, you cannot save the altered template back to disk
 from this point, to do so you must use the @{" template panel " link TemplatePanel}
 accessed from the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.
@endnode

@node FileReq "File Requester"
 The file requester in Presentation Master is much like the
 file requesters found in many other Amiga applications, and
 very similar in appearance and action to the standard file
 requester provided with the 2.0 operating system.  However,
 there are some additional features, and there are operational
 considerations one should be familiar with to fully utilize
 the requester:

    @{" Basic File Selection  " link FR_FileSelect}
    @{" Extension field       " link FR_Extension}
    @{" Open operation        " link FR_Open}
    @{" Save operation        " link FR_Save}
    @{" Device/Volume Listing " link FR_Devices}
    @{" Preview operation     " link FR_Preview}
    @{" Menus                 " link FR_Menus}
@endnode

@node FR_FileSelect "Help on Basic File Selection"
 Basic file selection in this file requester is similar to other
 file requesters.  When loading in a directory of file names,
 one can click on a desired file, or use the scroll bar, as
 desired.  Often, in a large directory, this saves much time
 as one does not have to wait for the entire directory to be
 loaded.

 Since it is difficult to click on a name if the list of names
 are constantly changing, the list will not be automatically
 updated once ten names are present in the requester.  If one
 wants the list updated, a simple click on the slider bar will
 cause it to happen.
@endnode

@node FR_Extension "Help on the Extension field"
 The extension field on the file requester is provided so one
 can specify an extension to use as a filter for what files are
 to be listed.  Note that all directories will always appear,
 only non-directory entries are effected.

 If the extension field is set to "pic" or ".pic" then only
 files ending in ".pic" will appear in the list.  This has
 nothing to do with the file name entered in the filename
 field, as you can enter anything you want.  The specified
 extension is NOT automatically appended to the file!
@endnode

@node FR_Open "Help on special handling in file Open operations"
 When the file requester is used to select a file to be opened,
 it will insist that the file be a valid existing file in order
 for you to exit using the "OK" button.  You can "Cancel" at
 any point, however.  Also the Open mode adds a @{" preview " link FR_Preview} area
 to the right side.

 In Open mode, one can simply double click on a file in the
 list in order to both select it and exit in the "OK" mode.
@endnode

@node FR_Save "Help on special handling in file Save operations"
 When the file requester is used to select a file to be saved,
 it will check to see if that file already exists and, if so,
 it will warn you that you will overwrite an existing file.

 In addition, to inhibit accidental misselection further, the
 double-click file selection is disabled.
@endnode

@node FR_Devices "Help on the Device, Volume, and Assign lists"
 When you parent to the top of the directory structure, you
 get three lists in sequence - a list of devices, volumes, and
 assigns.  The "Drives" button will jump immediately to the
 devices list.  The "Parent" button will cycle through the
 three lists.
@endnode

@node FR_Preview "Help on the Preview capability"
 When the file requester is in "Open" mode, an area appears to
 the right with a "Preview" button.  This area is used for
 previewing graphical files.  The exact types of files which
 can be previewed may vary at times, since this is controlled
 depending on the functionality required in a particular
 module, but the currently available code supports preview
 of the following types of files:
  * IFF ILBM and ANIM files.  For ANIM files, the first
    frame will be shown.  For both ILBM and ANIM files,
    the preview will be created from the full image unless
    a PRVW form exists on the file which contains the
    preview image already formed.  If you wish to save
    the preview image out to the file (ILBM files only)
    then there is a menu selection to do this.

  * SHOW file previews.  For Presentation Master SHO1 files,
    the first 6 @{" thumbnails " link G_Thumbnail} on the file will be shown.

  * EPS clipart file previews.  For EPS files which are in
    the PC format where a TIFF image is available on the
    file, the TIFF image will be previewed.  If the image is
    larger than the available preview area, then the upper
    left is shown and you can use the cursor keys to scroll
    the image around.
@endnode

@node FR_Menus "Help on the Menus"
 The file requester has a menu strip which provides the same
 functionality as the buttons as well as allowing deletion of
 files and drawers and the appending of preview images to
 ILBMs.

 Note that, while you can do so, it is not generally useful to
 append a preview image to a small brush.  The preview image
 often more than doubles the size of the IFF file and the loading
 and remapping of the brush itself is usually so fast that there
 is really not much to be gained.
@endnode

@node ImageLayer "Image Layer"
 An image layer permits importing an IFF picture or brush into
 a rectangular region on a slide.  One can import any resolution
 image including HAM, Extra Halfbrite, and even 8-bit and 24-bit
 images.  The source image is mapped to the pixel size of the
 layer and to the color palette of the slide (using dithering)
 for on-screen representation.  However, on output to @{" PostScript " link PostScript},
 the full resolution and original colors are restored to the image.

 There are options for controlling the aspect ratio and the color
 mapping of he image.  Also one may easily crop the image so only
 the desired sub-area of the image is displayed.

 There are three different control panels which may appear during
 edit of an image layer:

 @{" Tool Palette " link ImageTools}  @{" Import Panel " link ImageImport}  @{" Crop Panel " link ImageCrop}
@endnode

@node ImageTools "Image Layer Tool Palette"
 The tool palette for @{" image layers " link ImageLayer} is one of the simplest tool palettes
 in Presentation Master.  There are basically just three tools, beyond
 the normal "return" tool:

 @{" Import " link ImageImport}
   Used for the importing of IFF images to the layer.

 @{" Crop " link ImageCrop}
   Used to crop the existing IFF image to include only a portion.

 Redraw
   Used to remap the image to a different location and/or size of
   layer.  When this button is selected, the remap mode is forced
   to be "Map Image to Layer" so the existing image will be resized
   if necessary to the new layer size.

 Return
   This is the normal return tool which will transfer control to the
   slide sorter screen.  Note that if no IFF image has been imported,
   then you will be warned.
@endnode

@node ImageImport "Image Layer Import Panel"
   This panel permits you to select an IFF file and import it to the
   existing image layer.  You have selections over three remap
   controls:

      Size:  You can instruct Presentation Master to fit the image to
      the size of the existing layer, to resize the layer to match the
      original image (useful for brushes especially), or to shrink
      either the horizontal or vertical size of the layer to maintain
      the aspect ratio of the original image.

      Transparency:  You can instruct Presentation Master to make all
      colors opaque, so there are no transparent colors at all, or to
      make either color zero or the declared transparent color on the
      original @{" IFF " link G_IFF} image be transparent (if any).  Note that when
      outputting to #{" PostScript " link PostScript}, there is no such thing as transparency,
      so this is only for on-screen representations.  Also, the on-screen
      image is frozen for the complete image layer size at the time
      of import.  This means that transparent areas will not really
      be transparent in the future, but will contain whatever was
      behind them at the time of importing the image.

      Color Remap:  You can instruct Presentation Master to either just
      import the image directly, regardless of the RGB values of
      individual pixels in the original image, or to remap each pixel to
      the closest color in the current slide color palette.  The remapping
      of colors results in the best on-screen representation, but it is
      deceptive for PostScript.  When one outputs to PostScript, the
      original IFF image is loaded in and used for the PostScript image,
      whcih means that the original RGB colors of the image will be
      given to the PostScript device, regardless of which color remap
      selection was made at image import time.
@endnode

@node ImageCrop "Image Layer Image Cropping Panel"
   This panel permits you to crop an existing image in an image layer.
   When this panel is up, the outline presented with grab points is
   NOT the layer outline, but is rather a CROP boundary.  You move the
   sides around to enclose the area you want and then do a "Reimport"
   which will fill the existing layer boundary with the subsection of
   the picture you selected.  You may do this multiple times if you
   wish to get in closer and closer.  The image layer size MAY change
   if you have one of the size selections made where the layer will
   be altered to retain aspect.  If you wish to subsequently alter the
   size of the image, then exit this panel and use "Redraw" on the main
   @{" tool palette " link ImageTools}.

      Size:  You can instruct Presentation Master to fit the image to
      the size of the existing layer, to resize the layer to match the
      original image (useful for brushes especially), or to shrink
      either the horizontal or vertical size of the layer to maintain
      the aspect ratio of the original image.

      Transparency:  You can instruct Presentation Master to make all
      colors opaque, so there are no transparent colors at all, or to
      make either color zero or the declared transparent color on the
      original @{" IFF " link G_IFF} image be transparent (if any).  Note that when
      outputting to @{" PostScript " link PostScript}, there is no such thing as transparency,
      so this is only for on-screen representations.  Also, the on-screen
      image is frozen for the complete image layer size at the time
      of import.  This means that transparent areas will not really
      be transparent in the future, but will contain whatever was
      behind them at the time of importing the image.

      Color Remap:  You can instruct Presentation Master to either just
      import the image directly, regardless of the RGB values of
      individual pixels in the original image, or to remap each pixel to
      the closest color in the current slide color palette.  The remapping
      of colors results in the best on-screen representation, but it is
      deceptive for PostScript.  When one outputs to PostScript, the
      original IFF image is loaded in and used for the PostScript image,
      whcih means that the original RGB colors of the image will be
      given to the PostScript device, regardless of which color remap
      selection was made at image import time.
@endnode

@node TextLayer "Text and Title Layers"
 A text layer permits the entry of text into a rectangular region
 on the slide.  A title layer is just a special version of the
 text layer where there is a hot connection between the text and
 the name of the slide used on the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.

 Text can be left aligned, centered, or right aligned.  There is
 a @{" tool palette " link TextToolPalette} which provides easy control over many of the
 functions and more are provided in the menus.

 Text can be indented by placing tabs at the start of a line, and
 there are separate controls over the font, bullet, color, etc.,
 of three indention levels: no indent, single tab indent, and
 multiple tab indents.

 You can drag-select any section of text by pressing the mouse
 button down with the cursor at one point and then moving the
 cursor to a different point before releasing the mouse button.
 Also a double-click will select a word and a triple-click will
 select a paragraph.

 Text which has been selected may be cut with the DEL key or
 via the menu, and the contents of the cut buffer can be pasted
 back in at any point using the Shift-DEL key or the menu.  The
 selected text can also be altered in color and style (italic,
 bold, etc.).  You can also import ASCII text from a disk file
 into the cut buffer, to be subsequently pasted down at any
 desired point.

 The action of the mouse and cursor in a text layer is similar
 to many word processors.  See the manual for more info.

 N.B. that text is not rendered below the bottom of the layer.
 At times, if you are working on text near the bottom, the
 cursor or some valid text may dissappear from view.  Don't
 worry, it is still therre.  You can drag the bottom of the
 layer downward to view it if you wish.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyle "Help for the Object Style panel"
 The object style panel is invoked either from the menu in paint,
 or by a shift-click on any of the object creation tools in the
 tool palette.  It also is envoked from the object edit tool palette
 when clicking on the "S" tool (for "Settings") when editing a
 paint object or a composite object.

 This panel contains a number of areas for specific purposes:

            @{" Main Color " link ObjectStyleColor  }      @{" Line Width     " link ObjectStyleLW}
            @{" Shadow     " link ObjectStyleShadow }      @{" Polygon Entry  " link ObjectStylePolygon}
            @{" Edging     " link ObjectStyleEdge   }
            @{" Extrude    " link ObjectStyleExtrude}      @{" Open Rect Grid " link ObjectStyleGrid}
                 @{" Filled Rect Pattern " link ObjectStylePattern}
                 @{" Rounded Rect Radius " link ObjectStyleRadius}

 If you have invoked this panel from the editing system, trying to
 alter the look of an existing object, then there are some specific
 items that should be mentioned:
   1) The settings in the window will NOT necessarily reflect the
      current settings of any one subobject.  You are to set those
      items which are to be modified, and the changes will be
      propagated through all the subobjects.  The code will be able
      to recognize those settings you have changed by comparing with
      the value originally in the window.  If you want to change all
      objects to a value which is already shown in the window, then
      you have to change it to something else first, and exit the
      window with "OK" and then come back to the window and change
      it to the desired value.
   2) If any of the subobjects are text objects, then you cannot
      change their text attributes at this time.  The only exception
      to this is the color of the text.  You have to go down
      the heirarchy of the objects to one specific text object and
      alter its settings.  In this way you will be able to bring up
      a {" text settings " link TextStyle} window.  Also keep in mind that text color can
      only be set to one of the 16 base colors.  If you change color
      to one other than the 16 base colors, the color of any text
      objects will be set to the first color of the pair of colors
      which were dithered to get the selected color.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleColor "Help for setting Main Color of objects"
 This is the main color for the object.  If this is a compound object,
 you will be warned that all the subobjects will be changed in color,
 and given the opportunity to cancel it.  This is important, for
 example, if you try to recolor a piece of clipart.  This may change
 all elements to the same color, making the object look like a
 silhouette of the original object.

 If any subobjects are text objects, then they can only be set to
 one of the 16 base colors.  If you choose a color other than the
 base 16 colors, then text will be set to the first color of the
 color pair which was dithered to get the color.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleLW "Help for setting Line Width for Unfilled Objects"
 This is the Line Width for non-filled objects only.  The value is
 in pixels if positive, and in tenths of a point if negative.  If it
 is negative, then it will be rescaled if the object is resized.  If
 it is positive (in pixels) it will NOT be rescaled.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleShadow "Help for setting Shadow on an object"
 This area permits the addition of a shadow to any object.  The shadow
 will be in the color indicated, and will be offset from the main object
 by the specified dx,dy in PIXELS.  This dx,dy will NOT be rescaled if
 the object is resized.
@endnode

@node ObjectStylePolygon "Help for Regular Polygon parameters"
 These entries permit the specification of parameters for the regular
 polygon tool only.

 There are four parameters you can enter here:
   #Sides:      This is the number of sides for the polygon.
   Revolutions: This permits the number of sides to be drawn over
                multiple revolutions instead of just one.  For instance,
                five sides and two revolutions yields a five-pointed star.
   Init. Angle: This is the position to start drawing the polygon.  The
                value is in degrees measured clockwise from the 3 o'clock
                position of the circle.  Default is 0 degrees.  A value
                of 270 or -90 will start the polygon from the top.
   Deg./Sector: This is set automatically from the Revolutions value.
                When altering revolutions, you MUST set this to zero,
                since if non-zero, it is assumed that this is the value
                to use.  You can set this yourself to funky values.
                For instance, you may not let the polygon complete a full
                circle which causes strange shapes to occur, especially
                if you are drawing a spline polygon.
 N.B. that these entries ONLY apply to the regular polygon drawing tools.
      Also, they have no effect in editing an existing object, they only
      have effect on original creation of an object!
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleEdge "Help for setting object Edging"
 These entries allow the specification of an edging style for the object.
 Options include outline and emboss.  Outline is done at the specified
 width (in pixels) and in the first color specified.  Emboss is done at
 the specified width (in pixels) and the two colors indicate the bright
 and dark colors for an embossing which assumes a light source at the
 upper left of the screen.  For rectangles embossing is very fast and
 accurate.  For any other shapes, embossing is done by repeated drawing
 of the object in different colors and so may be slow and may lack the
 look desired at some times.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleExtrude "Help for setting object Extrude"
 These entries allow the specification of an extrusion for an object.  At
 present this only works on certain types of objects, due to the fact that
 this capability was put in primarily to support 3D bar and pie charts.

 There is an internal limitation to the number of panels in a given
 extrude of 1000.  If this is not adequate, then part of the extrude
 will not be there on the screen.  If necessary one can change the max
 numbers of panels in the extrude by putting the command "MAXEXTRUDE nnn"
 in the s:.PM.settings file, or a suitable project file, where "nnn" is
 the new size (e.g. "MAXEXTRUDE 3000").  If you don't have sufficient room
 to allocate the arrays necessary for the size selected, then Presentation
 Master will cut the size in half once and try again.  If it still cannot
 allocate all the ram necessary, then extrudes will not even be shown.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleGrid "Help for setting Grid in unfilled rectangles"
 These entries permit the specification of a grid to be formed in an
 open rectangle only.  This grid is formed at object creation and cannot
 be altered afterwards.  The values indicate the number of BOXES in the
 grid.  In other words, 1x1 is identical to 0x0 and gives just a simple
 open rectangle.  2x2 results in one subdivision into four boxes.

 N.B. That these settings have no effect in editing an existing object,
      they only have effect on original creation of an object!
@endnode

@node ObjectStylePattern "Help for setting Rectangle Fill Pattern"
 This entry permits the specification of a fill pattern for filled
 rectangles only.  Selections include solid (the default), and four
 gradations horizontal/vertical and single/double.  For solid fill
 the primary color at the top left of the screen is the color used.
 For all gradations, two colors are used and the gadget to the right
 is the secondary color.  Single gradations go from the primary color
 on the left or top to the secondary color at the right or bottom.
 Double gradations have the primary color in the center of the screen
 and the secondary color at the edges.
@endnode

@node ObjectStyleRadius "Help for setting Corner Radius for rectangles"
 This entry is for the radius of the corners of rounded-corner rectangles.
 The value is entered in pixels.

 N.B. That this setting has no effect in editing an existing object,
      it only has an effect on original creation of the object!
@endnode

@node TextStyle "Help for the Text Style panel"
 The text style panel is used both in painting, for entering text
 objects, as well as in the text layer.  In paint it is
 invoked via the menu or a shift-click on the text tool (or the
 "S" tool on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} when editing a text object).
 In a text layer it is invoked with the "S" tool on the text
 tool palette.

 The settings are shown on 3 lines.  The top one applies to
 non-indented text.  The second is for text indented with a
 single TAB.  The third is for multi-TAB indented lines.
 The left 4 buttons are for the bullet specification, where
 you select the character, color, outline, and shadow for
 the bullet.  The bullet and color selection is with @{" popup " link Popup}
 buttons.

 The rest of each line is devoted to the main text in the line.
 It allows selection of font, size, color, and style for the
 text.  Note that the color used for outline is unique for
 each line but is shared between the bullet and the main text.
 The color used for shadow is specified at the bottom of the
 panel and is shared for all shadowed text in the layer.

 Under 2.0 Operating System, you can directly alter the size
 of the text in the button provided and the text will be
 resized appropriately.  Normal Amiga fonts will not resize
 very well, since it is just remapping the @{" bitmap font " link BitmapFonts}
 images.  However, if you are using the @{" outline fonts " link OutlineFonts}
 provided with 2.0, then the resized font will look very
 smooth.
@endnode

@node Drawing "Object Based Draw System"
 Presentation Master contains an internal object based draw
 system which is competitive with many commercial draw programs.
 This permits drawn objects to be rendered to the full output
 resolution of the output device, such as a 300dpi laser
 printer.

 The paint system can be dealt with as two modes - the creation
 of new objects and the editing of existing objects.

 Object Creation:
    @{" Tool Palette            " link PaintToolPalette}
    @{" Style                   " link ObjectStyle}
    @{" Color palette           " link Colors}
    @{" Special Object Creation " link ObjectCreation}
 Object editing:
    @{" Edit Tool Palette       " link EditToolPalette}
@endnode

@node Colors
 Internally, Presentation Master maintains 24 bit colors when
 appropriate.  Since a 16-color Amiga hires screen is used for
 slide rendering during the design process, any colors other
 than the base 16 color palette are represented by dither
 combinations of pairs of the 16 base colors.

 The base 16 colors must be used for text and for specification
 of color gradations.  These can be revised via the @{" color edit window " link ColorEditWindow}.

 For paint operations, a 256 color palette is presented.  The
 top 16 colors in this palette are the base 16 colors.  The
 next 96 colors are transparent versions of the base colors.
 The transparent colors are in 6 sets: first two sets of 50%
 transparent which use a 50% @{" dither " link G_Dither}.  The difference between
 the two sets is that they use the opposite dither patterns.
 The other four sets are 25% transparent where each is a
 different dither pattern.  The different patterns allow the
 transparent colors to overlap with different results.
 N.B. that transparent colors are ONLY for on-screen rendering.
 @{" PostScript " link G_PostScript} does NOT do transparency, so they will NOT be
 transparent when output to slides or PostScript printers.

 The remaining colors in the 256 color palette are 50% dithers
 of all pair combinations of the 16 base colors.

 @{" process color " link ProcessColors} can be input via the Process Color window.
 This window is only accessable in ONE way in Presentation
 Master 1.0.  This is by doing a ALT-click on the color tool
 in the paint system.  When using this capability, CMYK values
 can be specified in 1% increments.

 24 bit RGB colors - Internally Presentation Master may keep a
 full 24 bit color for an object.  This happens in several
 instances.  One is in importing color clipart where the
 colors are converted to 24 bit RGB values.  Another is in
 morphing objects or just doing color interpolations over
 groupings of objects.  In these cases the end colors are
 determined and inbetween objects are set to interpolated
 24-bit RGB values.

 Note that in all cases, when a particular color is NOT just
 one of the 16 base colors, a best fit is made to the 16 base
 color palette to determine the best combination and dither
 percentage to use to represent the color.  This representation
 may be good or bad, depending on the suitability of the base
 color palette.
@endnode

@node ColorEditWindow "Color Edit Window"
 The Color Edit Window permits you to alter the RGB values for
 the base 16 colors for the Amiga display.  This permits altering
 the @{" RGB " link g_RGB} of any individual color, and also permits things like
 swapping two colors, copying one color value to another, and
 doing ranges of colors.  There is also a "rainbow" button which
 puts up a @{" HAM " link G_HAM} window showing all 4096 colors on the Amiga.  One
 can then put the mouse cursor over that range, hold down the left
 mouse button, and move the cursor around to see the selected
 color in the palette change in real time.  Also, when the
 rainbow window is NOT present, one can click on any color on
 the main part of the screen and the associated color index will
 be selected in the color edit window.  This permits quickly
 selecting a desired color for processing.

 N.B. that when you alter the RGB value of one or more colors in
 the base palette, it may alter the color appearance of some
 objects.  However, if they are specified via 24-bit RBG values,
 or @{" CMYK " link G_CMYK} process color values, then when they are redrawn, they
 will be represented, again, as their proper colors as best
 represented by the current base palette.  This may look better
 or worse, but those objects will not have their basic color
 values altered.  Objects which were drawn using the base 16
 colors will be altered in color by this window.
@endnode

@node ProcessColors "Process Color Selection Window"
 Process Colors can be specified via the Process Color window.
 This window is currently only invoked in ONE way - to do a
 ALT click on the color tool in paint.  The drawback is that
 one cannot edit these colors, one can only specify them upon
 object creation.  This will be rectified in the 1.1 release.
 This capability was left in for 1.0 since it was felt that it
 was better than not having it at all, but it will not be
 completely usable until 1.1!

 The process color window permits the input of either a 24-bit
 @{" RGB " link G_RGB} value or a @{" CMYK " link G_CMYK} value in 1% increments.  One can also load
 a color table and just pick colors out of the table.  Two
 tables are supplied, one of which has DIC colors.  A table for
 Pantone colors could be easily prepared, if one wishes, but
 the number of colors is so large that it is normally easier
 to just input the desired CMYK directly.  This too will be
 revised in 1.1 release.

 In the process color window are two color swatches.  One shows
 the specified color as accurately as possible.  The method is
 to do a 50% dither between two nearly identical colors so as to
 get a range of over 32000 colors which can be shown.  The second
 swatch shows how the color will appear on the screen utilizing
 the current 16 color base palette.  Note that the actual RGB
 or CMYK will be passed on to PostScript devices for accurate
 color rendering on slides or printed output.  However, on the
 screen we are limited by the 16 color palette of the Amiga and
 can only do our best with dithered pairs of those colors!
@endnode

@node ObjectCreation
 Presentation Master is a modular system in that many of its functions
 are relegated to external modules which can be added at will to
 expand the overall program capabilities.  One example of this is
 object creation.  Modules are provided to create various standard, but
 complex, objects such as bar charts, outline text, etc., and more will
 be provided in the future.

 Current creation modules include:

    Charts     - The Chart module can create bar/line/area/pie charts
                 from the users data, either imported or entered
                 directly into its spreadsheet-like datasheet.
    PolyText   - This module can create text paint objects given a
                 text string and a polygon font.  @{" Polyfonts " link OutlineFonts} are
                 proprietary fonts to Oxxi Inc., and are currently
                 used in several programs including Presentation Master
                 and VideoTitler.  There are utilities for converting
                 a variety of public font formats to polyfont format.
                 Text created in this manner can be manipulated as
                 any other paint object - bent, distorted, fit to a
                 circle, and even have its individual bezier points
                 edited.
    BulletText - This module is like PolyText except the text fonts
                 supported are the @{" Compugraphics Intellifonts " link OutlineFonts} utilized
                 by the Amiga 2.0 Operating System.  These fonts are
                 available from several Amiga publishing companies.
    ImportEPS  - This module imports an @{" EPS " link G_EPS} @{" clipart " link ClipArt} file, in Adobe
                 Illustrator format, as an editible object.  Most of
                 the commercial clipart available on the PC and Macintosh
                 platforms are in this format.  Many examples are
                 included with Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node ObjectEditing
 To edit an object, including moving, resizing, rotating, distorting,
 and any number of other detailed operations upon the object, one must
 first select it.  This is done with the selection tool in either the
 @"{ paint tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} or the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette}.  Once an object is
 selected, the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} is present so one can choose from
 a variety of operations.
@endnode

@node Align "Object Alignment Window"
 Object alignment permits aligning all subobjects of an object in
 various ways, including centering or aligning left, right, top,
 or bottom.  It can also force all objects to have the same size
 as well as providing equal spacing of interveining objects between
 the first and last subobjects.

 Also provided in this window are color and size interpolations.
 The color interpolation assigns 24-bit RGB values to all interveining
 objects, provided the end subobjects are of different colors.  The
 on-screen representation of these colors may leave a bit to be
 desired, due to having to approximate the colors with dithering and
 the base 16 color palette.  However, when output to devices that
 support more colors, the true RGB colors will be used.

 Morphing is also provided here.  This is a limited morph in that it
 requires the two objects to be constructed identically on a
 point-by-point basis.  The easiest way of achieving this is to
 create one object and then clone it and resize or otherwise revise
 the second object.  Just don't add or delete points or convert from
 spline to beziers unless you do the same to both objects.  Then
 group the two objects together and use this panel to create as many
 "tweens" as desired.
@endnode

@node Output
 Output
   Virtually all output capabilities in Presentation Master are
   carried out via output modules.  These are separate programs which
   are invoked and controlled from Presentation Master via messages.
   This permits the addition of new output capabilities with no
   change to the main program.

   Currently available output modules include:

      @{" Bitmap Print                    " link BitmapPrint}
      @{" PostScript                      " link PostScript}
      @{" IFF File Creation               " link MakeIFF}
      @{" 8-bit IFF File Creation         " link MakeIFF8} (optional)
      @{" ANIM File Creation and Tweening " link SaveANIM} (optional)
      @{" Vulcanization                   " link Vulcanize}
      @{" Export Outline                  " link ExportOutline}

   Another form of output available is to export a paint object as
   an @{" EPS " link G_EPS} file.  This is done with the optional @{" Export_EPS module " link ExportEPS}
   which is invoked from the paint edit system (since it has to be
   given a specific paint object for export).

   Other modules will be made available as needs arise and as the demand
   exists.
@endnode

@node ExportOutline
 Export Outline print module
   This module will prepare an ASCII outline of your presentation which
   can be printed.  There are options to control the amount of detail
   placed in the outline.
@endnode

@node BitmapPrint
 The Bitmap Print module simply does a dump of the screen to any Amiga
 Preferences supported graphics printer.  Output of this sort is limited
 by the screen resolution and color palette of the Amiga screen, namely
 640x400 (NTSC - or 640x512 PAL) and 16 colors (although dithering is
 used to achieve a much larger color palette).
@endnode

@node PostScript
 PostScript print module
 The PostScript print module provides @{" PostScript language " link G_PostScript} page descriptions
 either directly to a PostScript compatible device on the parallel, serial,
 or network print port, or to a disk file for later processing.  A wide
 variety of report formats are provided in this module including full
 slides, various storyboard formats from 2-up to 40-up, speaker note and
 audience handout reports.  One can also produce posters of any size by
 creating a matrix of pages, and one can create pages of labels of
 specified size.  In all cases, the output is to the full resolution of
 the output device and any included pictures will be to their full
 resolution and color palette.
@endnode

@node MakeIFF "Save_IFF"
 This module will create IFF files of any specified layered slides.
 If a branch of slides, or an entire slideshow, is specified, then they
 are given a sequence of file names with numbered extensions.
@endnode

@node MakeIFF8 "Save_IFF8 - (optional)"
 This module will create 8-bit IFF files of any specified layered slides.
 These IFF files contain images which may contain up to 256 colors
 on-screen (8-bits per pixel) and can be of various resolutions
 including (640x480), (1024x768), and (1280x1024).  This module also
 supports directly the Digital Micronics Resolver board so one can
 view any layered slide in 256 colors at the above resolutions (given
 an appropriate monitor).

 This module will be made available following the release of Presentation
 Master in a manner not yet determined.  Call Oxxi for details.

 If a branch of slides, or an entire slideshow, is specified, then they
 are given a sequence of file names with numbered extensions.
@endnode

@node Vulcanize
 The @{" Vulcanization " link G_Vulcanize} module creates stand-alone slideshows by converting
 all layered slides to IFF files.  All slide files are moved to a
 designated volume or volumes (such as one or more floppies) and a special
 show file is created which is stripped of unnecessary stuff and will
 run on a freely distributable slideshow program provided with
 Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node Quit
 Total, absolute, termination of the program!  Just make sure you have
 saved any work you have done prior to actually doing this.
@endnode

@node Memory
 Memory availability is key to keeping Presentation Master happy.
 Memory is used for LOTS of things, and is key to having the program
 run quickly, and even run at all.  When you get an indication that
 memory is running low, you should consider doing things to free up
 that memory.  If you have a lot of memory, but currently have it
 tied up with lots of slides in memory, then if possible you should
 save some of them out to disk and eliminate them from memory.
 Remember that when you put something into the @{" trashcan " link TrashCan}, it doesn't
 free up memory right away, so do something to get rid of it like
 trash an empty slide.

 If you are working with large shows, be sure to fully understand what
 it will get you to load the shows in @{" BRIEF " link G_Brief} mode.  This can save a
 lot of memory and still let you get the job done.

 If your machine isn't blessed with a lot of memory, there may still
 be hope.  Remember that a 2Mb stock Amiga 3000 really only has 1.5Mb
 at present since the system is placed in 1/2Mb of ram!  Thus this
 machine is really only a 1.5Mb machine!  Oxxi has stated that
 Presentation Master needs 2Mb of ram which excludes the 2Mb A3000
 at present (until the operating system is put back into ROM).
 However, one can sort of run at a very low and very tenuous level
 on such a machine.  However, to do so one must make certain
 concessions.  On any machine under 3Mb it is recommended that the
 overlay version of the program be installed, and on a 2Mb A3000
 this is imperative.  Also, during installation, choose the most
 severe memory conservation method, since you will need all you
 can get.  Consult the @{" Overlay " link Overlay} section for more info.
 The most effective solution to low memory is to add more memory.
@endnode

@node Overlay
 Upon installation a choice was made on installing the overlay or the
 non-overlay version.  If overlay was the choice, then a further choice
 was made on the level of memory conservation:
    1 - Full functionality
    2 - Conserve memory by dropping some internal buffers and some other
        means.
    3 - The most drastic.  This option deletes all internal buffers
        possible.  This means that at some times the background will
        not be displayed (for instance in the chart modules).  Also,
        there will be frequent redrawing of the slide, where the full
        functionality model saves various stages of the slide in
        internal buffers.  This level MAY run on a 2Mb A3000 where
        the 2.0 kickstart is loaded into ram from disk (effectively
        this is a 1.5Mb machine).  However, you will run into difficulty
        very quickly in such an environment.  It is STRONGLY recommended
        that more memory be added in such a machine.

 In all cases it is recommended that your machine have at least 3Mb of
 ram, exclusive of the 2.0 kickstart if appropriate.

 There are various actions you can take to help the situation if you
 have to operate in a small ram situation:

 1) Configure your operating system to minimize its ram requirements

   a) In the startup-sequence, remove all resident programs and cut
      extra disk buffers to a minimum.

   b) Remove or don't install extra drives.  For instance, an extra
      floppy plugged in requires about 20K extra.

   c) Don't install workbench (or if you do, at least make sure it is
      not interlaced and is only 4 or 2 color).  The easiest way to
      eliminate workbench is to go to the startup-sequence and remove
      the "loadwb" and "endcli" statements at the end.  This will leave
      you in the CLI which requires running PMaster by the command
      "PMaster".  Most people cannot do this, but at least make sure
      you havn't made the workbench interlaced, nor have you added more
      colors to it.  This will only take up valuable memory!

   d) Under 2.0, do not use the large diskfont.library which supports
      the Compugraphic outline fonts.  This library is around 50K where
      the original, smaller, one is only around 8K!

   e) It helps to boot up under 1.3 on an A3000.  This will probably gain
      around 100K depending on your exact configuration (on an A2000 1.3
      will gain 1/2Mb over 2.0 if 2.0 is loaded into ram from disk).  On
      an A3000 1/2Mb is used in ram for either the 2.0 or 1.3 kickstart
      image so that is not where you gain memory.

      If you use 2.0 on your A3000 for everything, then you can configure
      your startup-sequence for 1.3 to not load workbench, eliminate
      resident programs, and in general do everything you can to minimize
      ram usage.  Then boot under 1.3 when you want to run PMaster.  Just
      make sure that if you installed PMaster while under 2.0, you move the
      @{" s:.PM.settings " link PMsettings} file to the s: directory used by 1.3.

   f) If you have a lot of fonts, then make a second fonts drawer with only
      the fonts you need for PMaster.  This will reduce the size of internal
      tables of fonts/sizes used within PMaster.  You just have to remember
      to reassign fonts: to the other drawer when running PMaster.

 2) Use Practical Restraints in the Use of Presentation Master:

   a) Do not load/create large presenatations with many slides of the
      layered type.  Obviously, the more slides in a show, the more ram
      that is required.  Utilize BRIEF mode of file loading as much
      as possible.

   b) Some clipart can be extremely large.  Since PMaster converts clipart
      into structured editable objects, the draw commands to reproduce some
      clipart can consume large amounts of ram.  Keep this in mind and don't
      use large, or any, clipart when ram is limited.

   c) Templates can also take up ram.  The diamonds1 template is around
      145K in size.  Others are 20K and up in size.  You can do a lot of
      work with no template loaded at all (there is a built-in template
      to use when one isn't loaded).  This takes a bit more work, but will
      help out with ram.  A NULL template will be provided which can be
      loaded to eliminate the ram a template occupied once you are through
      with it, if necessary.  When a template is opened in BRIEF mode,
      this saves quite a bit of ram.  However, when you create a new
      layered slide, the full template data for the selected template
      will be loaded from disk and placed in the new slide.  Therefore,
      one still should avoid large templates.

   e) Avoid lots of different fonts/sizes.  Each font used requires memory
      (especially important if it is a large size).  It is extremely easy
      to consume large blocks of ram by specifying different large point
      sizes with outline fonts.

   f) Avoid image layers - especially large ones.  The image in each image
      layer is held in ram at present in uncompressed form for raapid
      blitting of the image.  For instance, a full screen image layer will
      use 128,000 bytes of ram!  IFF backdrops don't have this overhead,
      but using IFF backdrops is still a stressing operation and time-
      consuming as well on the low-memory mode of operation, so their use
      is not recommended in low ram.

   g) Don't fill up the clipboard with lots of stuff.  Remember, it's still
      in ram even if it's in the clipboard!

   h) Remember, the last item placed in the trashcan will stay in ram so
      you can retrieve it if you wish (like an UNDO of trashing a show!).
      If you really want to eliminate something from memory, put it into
      the trashcan and then trash an empty slide.  The simplest way to do
      that is to click on the empty slide stack, creating a new slide at
      the start of the rack of children.  Then simply drag this new
      empty slide to the trashcan, which will delete what was previously
      in the trashcan.

   i) Finally - Save Your Work FREQUENTLY!!  While there are safeguards to
      make PMaster handle low memory graciously, there will undoubtedly be
      circumstances out of our control which could hang or even crash the
      system.  It is your responsibility to make sure that if this happens
      the loss is a minimum.
@endnode

@node Popup "PopUp Buttons"
 There are two basic types of popup buttons used in Presentation
 Master:

    @{" PopUp Menu Buttons" link PopupMenuButtons}
       Designated by a downward pointing triangle on a small active
       button on the left end of the button.
    @{" PopUp Color Buttons" link PopupColorButtons}
       Designated by four colored dots on a small active button
       on the left end of the button.

 Both operate essentially the same.  To the left end is the active
 button and the remainder of the button is inactive and displays
 the current selection.

 You use them in either of 2 ways:

   1) Position the cursor on the active part of the button and press
      down the LEFT mouse button.  The popup should appear.

      Then, with the mouse button depressed, move the cursor over
      the desired selection and release the mouse button.

      Should you choose to cancel the selection, just move the cursor
      off the menu and release the button.

   2) The same as above except you click on the active part of the
      button.  The menu will popup and stay up.  You then simply click
      on the selected item, or off the menu for a cancel.
@endnode

@node PopupMenuButtons
 Presentation Master uses PopUp buttons a LOT.  This is due to the
 ease of selecting from an often large list of selections, but
 when not in use the only space required on the screen is the
 button which shows the current selection.

 Sometimes (like the popup for fonts) the popup will scroll (move
 the cursor to the up/down arrows at the top/bottom of the menu)
 and may also have popup sub-menus (like text size in the font
 popup).
@endnode

@node PopupColorButtons
 There are two types of color popups - a 16 color popup for when
 one has to select only from the base fixed palette, and a 256
 color popup for paint when dithered pairs and transparent colors
 are acceptable.  Note that colors in the 256 color palette
 that show a "T" through the color are transparent.
@endnode

