@node G_Amiga "Amiga computer"
 Amiga - Spanish word for friend (feminine).  Also the name of the best
         personal computer made.  However, the existence of this computer
         seems to be a secret known only to a small portion of the
         community.
@endnode

@node G_AnnotPaint "Annotation Paint"
 Annotation Paint - This is a full-screen paint layer which is always
                    present on any layered slide over the top of all other
                    layers.  Its main intent is to allow the addition of
                    any annotation to a slide easily and quickly.
@endnode

@node G_ASCII "ASCII"
 ASCII - The "American Standard Code for Information Interchange" assigns
         a specific code to each digit, letter, and control character,
         including the "diacritical" characters.
@endnode

@node G_ANIM "ANIM file format"
  ANIM file format
   This is the de facto standard animation file format for the Amiga
   computer.  Actually this is an @{" IFF " link G_IFF} file format which consists of
   a single FORM ANIM.  The first frame is a standard FORM ILBM so
   if you open an ANIM file into a paint program, usually the first
   frame will be loaded.  Following the standard FORM ILBM will be
   a variable number of additional FORMs ILBM which are, in reality,
   not legitimate ILBMs at all, but are instead delta representations
   of each frame.  For more information, consult the ANIM file format
   specification available from Commodore.
@endnode

@node G_Backdrop "Backdrop"
 Backdrop - The backdrop color, fill pattern, or IFF file which
            provides the background behind all paint, text, images, etc.,
            in a layered slide.
@endnode

@node G_BackPaint "Background (or Template) Paint"
 Background Paint - The full-screen paint layer which appears immediately
                    over the backdrop and is the bottom-most layer of
                    any layered slide.  This provides the background
                    graphics over which the rest of the layers of a
                    layered slide are rendered.  Normally the content of
                    this layer is pre-drawn and provided with the
                    template.  For this reason this layer is sometimes
                    referred to as the template paint layer.
@endnode

@node G_Bezier "Bezier curve"
Bezier -
 A Bezier curve is a curve defined by the two end points and one or
 more control points which cause the line to bend.  In Presentation
 Master we utilize 4-point beziers in which there are two anchor
 points (the end points of the curve) and two control points (each
 of which is associated with one of the end points).  The control
 points, along with their associated end points, define the tangents
 at the end of the curve, and their length (from the anchor to the
 control point) determine how strongly the tangent will effect the
 overall curvature of the curve as it leaves the anchor point.

 It is really quite easy to achieve a wide variety of curved shapes
 by moving the four points around in various ways.

 Beziers can be obtained in Presentation Master in two ways:
   1) by @{" converting " link EP_Convert} an object like a line or @{" spline " link G_Spline} to a bezier.
   2) by importing or creating an object that already has
      beziers as part of the object.  For example, an imported
      piece of clipart or a created pie chart or string of
      polygon text characters.
 There is no direct tool to create a bezier in Presentation Master.
 This is intentional, since bezier tools are often confusing and
 the spline tools in Presentation Master are much easier to use.
 If you really want to generate a bezier, do the following.  First
 draw an object such as a rectangle, a straight line, or a sequence
 of lines.  Then select the object and use the @{" convert to bezier " link EP_Convert} tool
 to change it to beziers.  You can then use the 'E' tool in the
 @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} to edit the individual bezier control points and
 anchor points.
@endnode

@node G_BlackHole "Black Hole"
 Black Hole - An alternate image for the familiar trashcan in the slide
              sorter screen.  To change the trashcan to a black hole,
              simply type a shift-help while in the slide shorter.
@endnode

@node G_BlackSlide "Black Slides"
 Black Slides

    This is simply a black screen.  This is useful for on-screen
    presentations.  For instance it could be a holding point for the
    presenter to be able to talk directly to his audience.  One can
    place @{" narration " link Narration} on a black slide.
@endnode

@node G_Brief Brief
  Brief - When loading a show file into Presentation Master, there
          is frequently much memory taken up with tables of drawing
          information.  When a show is loaded in BRIEF, this drawing
          information is left on disk, with only the @{" thumbnail " link G_Thumbnail}, and
          various information such as transition for slideshow
          being loaded into memory.  This greatly reduces the space
          required in memory.  Presentation Master will retrieve the
          necessary information from disk when necessary for slide
          editing, saving a new show file, or other operations where
          this data is required.  For many operations one does not
          require this data in memory.  This permits the manipulation
          and creation of very large slideshows with a minimum of
          memory.
@endnode

@node G_BulletFont "Bullet Font"
 Bullet Font - This is a synonym for Compugraphic @{" Intellifonts " link G_Intellifont}.  Actually
               the term isn't used with the Amiga any more, but was
               retained here due to its brevity.  Bullet fonts are those
               distributed by Commodore (with the 2.0 system), Gold Disk,
               and others, and may be utilized by the BulletText module.
@endnode

@node G_Child "Child"
 Child - In the heirarchical nature of both slides and objects in
         Presentation Master, a child is a slide or object which is below
         another slide or object in the heirarchy.  Viewed as a tree,
         this term refers to the branches which leave a given slide or
         object.
@endnode

@node G_ChipRam "Chip Memory"
 Chip Memory - In the Amiga there are two types of memory, Chip and Fast.
               Chip memory is the memory which can be accessed by special
               custom chips within the Amiga hardware which includes
               video display.  The images displayed on the screen on the
               Amiga have to be present in Chip memory.  Fast memory
               cannot be accessed by these custom chips, but by this very
               fact are also "faster" in operation since they are not
               slowed down by conflicts caused by these chips.  Normally
               the bulk of the memory on an Amiga is Fast memory.  Chip
               memory is restricted normally to the first 1/2, 1, or 2 Mb
               of memory in the machine, depending on configuration.
@endnode

@node G_Clipboard "Clipboard"
 Clipboard - In Presentation Master, a "holding area" in which slides,
             segments of shows, or complete shows can be stored and in
             which the thumbnail image of the parent slide can be viewed.
             Shows can be loaded directly to the clipboard or saved to
             disk directly from the clipboard.
@endnode

@node G_CMYK "CMYK color model"
  CMYK - This is a color model based on the process colors Cyan,
         Magenta, Yellow, and Black.  In Presentation Master one can
         specify CMYK color values in 1% steps in each component
         from 0% to 100%.  This is done in the @{" Process Color " link ProcessColors} window.
@endnode

@node G_COLO "Colo"
  Colo - Abbreviation for "Color" used in text on cover of Presentation
         Master box.
@endnode

@node G_Commodore "Commodore"
 Commodore - The computer company which manufactures the @{" Amiga " link G_Amiga} computer
             but often seem to not want to let people know about it.
             Sincere thanks go to many of the Commodore people who have
             supported and assisted in the creation of Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node G_ContentLayer "Content Layer"
 Content Layer - This refers collectively to all the text, title, graphic,
                 and image layers which exist between the background paint
                 layer and the annotation paint layer.  These generally
                 contain the "content" of the slide (where the background
                 paint layer contains general background designs from the
                 template and annotation paint is for the addition of
                 extra annotation comments or graphics).
@endnode

@node G_Cusp "Cusp"
 Cusp - In a @{" spline " link G_Spline} curve, this is a point which is a "corner" or, in
        other words, breaks the curve between two splines or lines.  This
        is opposed to a @{" Node " link G_Node} which is a smooth transition point along
        a continuous spline curve.
@endnode

@node G_Dither Dithering
  Dithering - This refers to the process where two or more colored
              pixels are alternated in a pattern to approximate
              an in-between color.  This technique allows Presentation
              Master to approximate any 24-bit RGB value using two
              of the colors in the fixed 16 color palette.  This
              technique can sometimes give colors which are not
              distinguishable from the desired color, and other times
              will give very offensive combinations of patterns of
              colored dots.  However, remember that while this is
              used to approximate colors on the screen, when the
              slide is output to color @{" PostScript " link PostScript}, the proper color
              will be shown.
@endnode

@node G_EHB "Extra Halfbrite display mode"
  Extra Halfbrite - This is a technique used on the Amiga for getting
              more colors (64 in fact) on a @{" low resolution " link G_lores} picture which
              is normally limited to 32 colors.  Presentation Master
              will not generate such pictures, but you can select such
              a picture to be shown as an @{" IFF slide " link ImageSlide}.
@endnode

@node G_EmptySlide "Empty Slides"
Empty Slides
    These are merely place-holders in the tree structure of the
    presentation.  They are not displayed in on-screen slideshows,
    nor do they generate output, except in the storyboard form of
    @{" PostScript " link PostScript} output.

    Double-click on an Empty Slide to create one of the other, more
    useful, slide types from it.
@endnode

@node G_EPS "EPS files"
  EPS - This stands for Encapsulated @{" PostScript " link PostScript} @{" clipart " link Clipart} files.
        In Presentation Master, EPS files can be loaded provided the
        EPS is in Adobe Illustrator format.  This format is well
        documented and accounts for the vast majority of EPS clipart
        available on the PC and Macintosh platforms.  Presentation
        Master can open these EPS files as fully editable objects in
        the paint system, which permits the user to alter individual
        elements of the clipart and/or to do things like resize, rotate,
        distort, etc., of the object.  Also, the artwork appears to
        maximum possible resolution on the screen so it is suitable for
        on-screen slideshows and for output to bitmap printers.

        If the file has a @{" PC TIFF " link G_TIFF} preview (@{" EPSF File " link G_EPSF}) then one can see
        the preview image within the file requester prior to actually
        importing the image.
@endnode

@node G_EPSF "EPSF files"
  EPSF - This is a special version of an @{" EPS " link G_EPS} file which contains a preview
         image as a binary @{" TIFF " link G_TIFF} image at the end of the file.  The file
         also contains a 30 byte binary header at the start of the file
         identifying it as an EPSF file.  These files are primarily used
         on the PC platform and comprise the majority of commercial
         clipart available on the PC.  Presentation Master can read in
         these previews and display them on the file requester so one
         can see what the EPSF file is prior to actually importing it.
         In addition, the @{" ExportEPS " link ExportEPS} module can generate EPSF files.
@endnode

@node G_EPSI "EPSI files"
  EPSI - This is a special version of an @{" EPS " link G_EPS} file which contains a preview
         image in ASCII comments at the start of the file.  Presentation
         Master cannot use such previews, but they can be generated by
         the @{" ExportEPS " link ExportEPS} module for use on other systems (like UNIX).
@endnode

@node G_FastRam "Fast Memory"
 Fast Memory - In the Amiga there are two types of memory, Chip and Fast.
               Chip memory is the memory which can be accessed by special
               custom chips within the Amiga hardware which includes
               video display.  The images displayed on the screen on the
               Amiga have to be present in Chip memory.  Fast memory
               cannot be accessed by these custom chips, but by this very
               fact are also "faster" in operation since they are not
               slowed down by conflicts caused by these chips.  Normally
               the bulk of the memory on an Amiga is Fast memory.  Chip
               memory is restricted normally to the first 1/2, 1, or 2 Mb
               of memory in the machine, depending on configuration.
@endnode

@node G_Gridsnap "Grid Snap"
 Grid Snap - This is the process of having a grid defined and having all
             x,y positions in drawing objects fall precisely on that grid.
             This is invaluable in the alignment and arrangement of multiple
             objects.
@endnode

@node G_Group "Group"
 Group - This is the process of linking two or more objects together so they
         can be treated as a single object.  This allows resizing,
         distortion, rotation, alignment, morphing, etc., to take place
         on the subobjects as a unit.  Some objects are pre-grouped upon
         creation or importing them.  For example charts (bar and pie),
         polygon and bullet text, and clipart.
@endnode

@node G_HAM "HAM Display Mode"
  HAM Display Mode
   HAM stands for Hold And Modify and is a special form of on-screen
   graphics representation on the Amiga which permits showing all
   possible 4096 colors on-screen at once.  This is done by making
   any given pixel either be a fixed color from a 16 color palette,
   or making it the same as the preceeding pixel with the Red, Green,
   OR Blue component altered.  Thus to show all colors, one has to
   derive most colors from a different color by altering the different
   components.  This results in what is referred to as "HAM fringing"
   where smears of in-between colors appear at the borders between
   two colors when the second color isn't easily achieved.  The quality
   of a HAM picture depends on code in the creation program to
   optimize the fixed portion of the palette so as to minimize the
   most objectionable fringing, however if there are many colors in
   the picture, then it is impossible to totally eliminate fringing.
   Presentation Master can show HAM pictures as @{" IFF slides " link ImageSlide}, but has no
   ability to generate HAM pictures.  In fact, HAM is restricted to
   @{" lores " link G_lores} pictures, and Presentation Master creates layered slides
   only as @{" hires " link G_hires} pictures.
@endnode

@node G_hires "hires display resolution"
  hires display resolution

   On the Amiga, hires refers to the horizontal resolution which yields
   640 pixels in a non-overscan display.  In this resolution, the Amiga
   can display 16 colors maximum.  This is the resolution used in
   Presentation Master for creation of layered slides.  Presentation
   Master utilizes @{" dithering " link G_Dither} techniques to represent a much larger
   palette on the screen.
@endnode

@node G_HotSpot "Hot Spots"
 Hot Spots - This is the capability of defining rectangular regions on a
             parent slide which are "bound" to particular child slides.
             Then in a manual slideshow, upon clicking with the mouse on
             one of these hotspots, the child slide will be displayed.
             This permits one to have "backup" slides to support details
             on another slide.  Then one does not even have to show them
             if no one is interested in that level of detail.  However,
             they are there to support questions when necessary.  This
             also allows the building of interactive shows for training,
             kiosks, etc.
@endnode

@node G_IFF "IFF file format"
  IFF file format

   IFF stands for Interface File Format and is a standard format for
   various types of files on the Amiga computer, and also on some other
   platforms.  Note that an IFF file is NOT automatically a picture.
   Often a picture is referred to as an IFF file, while in reality is
   is normally an @{" IFF FORM ILBM " link G_ILBM} file.  Animations are normally on
   @{" IFF FORM ANIM " link G_ANIM} files.  There are also IFF formats for sampled sounds,
   and text files as well as other things.  The SHOW files used by
   Presentation Master are IFF FORM SHO1 files.  For more details,
   one is referred to the IFF standard published by Commodore.
@endnode

@node G_ILBM "IFF FORM ILBM file format"
  ILBM file format

    This stands for InterLeave BitMap which is a format for storing display
    information where the information from all bitplanes for a given scan
    line are stored together.  See the IFF specification from Commodore
    for more information.  The ILBM form is the normal storage form for
    pictures in the IFF file format on the Amiga.
@endnode

@node G_ImageLayer "Image Layer"
 Image Layer - This is one of the types of possible content layers of a
               slide (Text, Title, Graphic, and Image layers).  This permits
               placing an IFF image or brush into a designated area of
               a slide.  For on-screen display, the resolution and colors
               will be best-fit to the screen.  However, when output to
               PostScript, the full resolution and proper colors will
               be used.
@endnode

@node G_ImageSlide "Image or IFF Slide"
Image or IFF Slides

    These can contain any displayable @{" IFF " link G_IFF}  picture or @{" ANIM " link G_ANIM} file.  Those
    files which are displayable at present are lores/hires and interlace/
    non-interlace.  This includes all of what are considered the
    "normal" Amiga display modes (including @{" HAM " link G_HAM} and @{" Extra Halfbrite " link G_EHB}).
    One can place 8-bit and 24-bit pictures into such a slide if they
    are simply going to be output to @{" PostScript " link PostScript}.  However these cannot
    be displayed by the Presentation Master slideshow module.
@endnode

@node G_Intellifont "Intellifont"
 Intellifont - This is one of the names used for the outline fonts which
               are included with the Amiga 2.0 system.  The full name
               is Compugraphic Intellifont and they are sometimes referred
               to as @{" Bullet " link G_BulletFont} fonts.  These are used in two ways by
               Presentation Master.  First, the 2.0 system uses them for
               providing bitmap fonts of high quality at any designated
               size, and Presentation Master makes full use of this.
               Second, there is a Bullet Font module which allows the
               creation of paint objects representing any text string
               rendered in with a given Intellifont.
@endnode

@node G_Interlace "Interlace"
 Interlace - This is the effect seen on NTSC and PAL video displays where
             every other scan line on the screen is rendered in one field
             (in 1/60 sec in NTSC or 1/50 sec in PAL) and the in-between
             scan lines are rendered on the next field (the next 1/60
             or 1/50 sec interval).  Thus the entire display is refreshed
             every 1/30 or 1/25 sec.  However, if adjacent scan lines
             differ in brightness significantly, then there will be a
             flicker seen which can be very objectionable.  On the Amiga
             3000 one can use a MultiScan monitor and avoid this problem.
             On other Amigas, there are "Flicker Fixers" which permit the
             use of a MultiScan monitor as well. Without a MultiScan
             monitor, Presentation Master will attempt to reduce flicker
             by altering its rendering rules a bit.  For instance horizontal
             black and white lines outlining buttons will be doubled so
             they won't flicker as much.  Also dither patterns will often
             be modified a bit to double pixels up.
@endnode

@node G_Landscape "Landscape"
 Landscape - A page orientation in which the slide is rendered with the
             long dimension of the paper as the horizontal dimension of
             the slide, resulting in a slide which has a predominantly
             horizontal orientation.  Note that this is the normal
             orientation for a computer screen and the normal orientation
             for most slide and overhead presentations.  Presentation
             Master normally operates in this orientation, but can do
             other sizes if desired.
@endnode

@node G_LayeredSlide "Layered Slide"
 Layered Slide - This is one of the four basic slide types: @{" Empty Slide " link G_EmptySlide},
                 @{" Black Slide " link G_BlackSlide}, @{" IFF Slide " link ImageSlide}, and @{" Layered Slide " link LayeredSlide}.
@endnode

@node G_LineWidth "Line Width"
 Line Width - This is the width to be used in rendering a line.  In
              Presentation Master there are two ways of specifying line
              width.  If positive, the width is in screen pixels and will
              be scaled appropriately in PostScript output.  If negative,
              the absolute value is assumed to be in tenths of a point!
              Several items should be noted:
                1 - When specified in tenths of a point (negative width)
                    the line will ALWAYS be rendered as a single pixel
                    width on the screen, but will be ok in PostScript.
                2 - When the display is zoomed (either in or out) all
                    lines are rendered a 1 pixel width.
                3 - With current rendering algorithms (due to be improved
                    soon) wide line widths are quite slow to render
                    on the screen.
@endnode

@node G_lores "lores display resolution"
 lores display resolution

   On the Amiga, lores refers to the horizontal resolution which yields
   320 pixels in a non-overscan display.  In this resolution, the Amiga
   can display 32 colors maximum except for @{" Extra Halfbrite " link G_EHB} mode and
   @{" HAM " link G_HAM} mode.
@endnode

@node G_Narration "Narration"
 Narration - This is the process of using the Amiga Narration device to
             recite a block of text.  This narration leaves a lot to be
             desired, but is of tremendous help at times.  Future release
             will support sampled sounds for high-quality voice tracks
             as well as music.
@endnode

@node G_Node "Node"
 Node - In a @{" spline " link G_Spline} curve, this is a point which is smooth or, in
        other words, is a continuous point along a curved line.  This is
        opposed to a @{" Cusp " link G_Cusp} which is a break in the curve and allows
        corners and straight lines to be inserted into a curve path.
@endnode

@node G_NTSC "NTSC"
 NTSC - The video/television standard used in the United States as well as
        some other areas of the world.  In this mode the Amiga screen is
        400 lines high (non-overscan).  Presentation Master will determine
        automatically the display type (NTSC or @{" PAL " link G_PAL}) and set its bitmaps
        accordingly.  If you wish to override this, one can place the
        command "NTSC" or "PAL" on the @{" s:.PM.settings " link PMsettings} file, or any project
        file for Presentation Master, and the program will be forced into
        the selected screen size.
@endnode

@node G_Object "Object"
 Object - A single drawn item in the graphics paint system.  The paint
          system in Presentation Master is "Object Based" which means that
          each item is retained as a series of drawing instructiions so
          it can be redrawn and/or modified as desired.
@endnode

@node G_PaintLayer "Paint Layer"
 Paint Layer - This is one of the types of possible content layers of a
               slide (Text, Title, Graphic, and Image layers).  This permits
               placing a graphics region anywhere on a layered slide.
@endnode

@node G_PAL "PAL"
  PAL - The video/television standard used in most countries in Europe and
        many other areas of the world.  In this mode the Amiga screen is
        512 lines high (non-overscan).  Presentation Master will determine
        automatically the display type (@{" NTSC " link G_NTSC} or PAL) and set its bitmaps
        accordingly.  If you wish to override this, one can place the
        command "NTSC" or "PAL" on the @{" s:.PM.settings " link PMsettings} file, or any project
        file for Presentation Master, and the program will be forced into
        the selected screen size.
@endnode

@node G_Parent "Parent slide"
 Parent - In the heirarchical structure of either an object or a slideshow,
          every slide may have child slides.  That slide is then referred
          to as the "Parent" of each of those child slides.
@endnode

@node G_Pixel "Pixel"
 Pixel - A single unit of color on the screen.  This is the smallest unit
         of information on a display.
@endnode

@node G_Point Point
  Point - When applied to printing, a Point is 1/72.xxx inch.  This
          traditional definition as been revised for computer usage
          in which case a point is defined as 1/72 inch exactly.  In
          Presentation Master, points are used primarily as a dimension
          which corresponds to the printed page on @{" PostScript " link PostScript} output
          devices.  In the selection of fonts, the size is NOT points,
          but rather is in terms of the height of the font in pixels.
          The difference is not large, but is not negligible.  For
          instance, the printed page is typically around 500 points
          high while on the screen it is represented as 400 pixels
          high (in NTSC).
@endnode

@node G_PolyFont "Polygon Font"
 PolyFont - This is a proprietary @{" outline font " link OutlineFonts} format used in Presentation
            Master and Oxxi VideoTitler 3D.  These are accessed by the
            PolyFont module from within a paint layer and are created as
            a series of objects for the letters of a character string.
@endnode

@node G_Portrait "Portrait orientation}
 Portrait - A page orientation in which the slide is rendered with the
            long dimension of the paper as the vertical dimension of
            the slide, resulting in a slide which has a predominantly
            vertical orientation.
@endnode

@node G_PostScript "PostScript Language"
  PostScript Language
      The PostScript language is a simple interpretive programming
      language with powerful graphics capabilities.  Its primary
      application is to describe the graphic appearance of a printed
      page.  It can also be used to describe appearance of other
      forms of output such as 35mm slides.  The @{" PostScript " link PostScript} module
      in Presentation Master generates PostScript language files
      for output to printers or @{" slide service bureaus " link SlideService}.  For more
      information on the PostScript language, consult one of the
      many books on the subject.
@endnode

@node G_Prefs "Preferences"
 Preferences - User settings which are used in the initial running of
               Presentation Master or a given module.  Master preferences
               are contained in the @{" s:.PM.settings " link PMsettings} file and may be
               altered using the @{" PMprefs " link PMprefs} program.  Project preferences
               may also be used by saving a project file after setting
               things up the way one wishes.  Module preferences are
               normally saved automatically to remember the settings the
               last time a module was used, so the next time will look
               substantially the same.  In addition the @{" PostScript " link PostScript} module
               uses a system of Printer Settings files to provide settings
               peculiar to a given printer.
@endnode

@node G_Preview "Image Preview"
 Preview - The file requester has the ability to provide a graphic preview
           of certain file types prior to actually selecting the file for
           use in Presentation Master.  This ability extends to @{" IFF " link G_IFF} files
           (first frame only for @{" ANIM " link G_ANIM} files) and to Presentation Master
           @{" SHO1 " link G_SHOW} files as well as to @{" EPSF " link G_EPSF} files.
@endnode

@node G_RemapColors "Color Remapping"
 Remap Colors - This is the process of taking a desired color, often a
                24-bit RGB color or a CMYK color, and making a best
                approximation using the base 16 colors on the screen
                and using dithering patterns.  For images this is
                necessary to do a reasonable replication of the original
                image on the screen which has ususally a different color
                palette.  However, the full desired colors will be sent
                to color PostScript devices so they will have fully
                accurate colors.
@endnode

@node G_Resolution "Resolution"
 Resolution - The degree of detail that can be displayed on screen or
              reproduced on the printed output.
@endnode

@node G_RGB "RGB Color Model"
 RGB - This is the most common color model used in computer graphics
       and the one which is native to the Amiga.  This stands for
       Red, Green, and Blue.  Normally on the Amiga one can specify
       each component as a value between 0 and 15 where 15 is full
       brightness of a particular component.  Thus black is (0,0,0)
       and white is (15,15,15).  In Presentation Master one can
       create objects which have 24-bit RGB values which means that
       each component is of a value from 0 to 255 (8 bits per
       component).  This provides a total of over 16 Million colors.
       24-bit RGB values will be on color objects imported in ClipArt
       files and also will be assigned to objects where color have
       been interpolated such as is done out of the @{" alignment panel " link Align}.

       24-bit RGB values can also be assigned via the @{" Process Color " link ProcessColors} window.
@endnode

@node G_Sibling "Sibling"
 Sibling - In a heirarchical tree structure, such as is used for both
           slides and objects in Presentation Master, this refers to an
           object or slide which is alongside a given object/slide
           in the tree (i.e. they both have the same parent slide).
@endnode

@node G_Slide "Slide"
 Slide - A single screen image in Presentation Master which is
         either created or imported for one position in a presentation.
         Each slide can have child slides and is thought of as including
         all of these child slides and all their child slides in turn.
@endnode

@node G_SlideSorter "Slide Sorter screen"
 @{" Slide Sorter " link SlideSorter} - This is the main controlling screen for Presentation
                Master from which the entire presentation is created and
                controlled.
@endnode

@node G_ShowANIM "ShowANIM program"
 ShowANIM - a player program for ANIM and still IFF files which is
            included with Presentation Master.  One of the nice ways to
            use this program is as the default tool on the icon for a
            still or ANIM IFF file.  Normally, this is the default
            tool automatically placed on an icon by Presentation
            Master when a picture or animation is created.  To see
            a list of the tool types appropriate for controlling
            ShowANIM from an icon, simply click on the ShowANIM icon
            itself.  To see the command line arguments which are
            recognized, simply run ShowANIM, without a file, from the
            CLI shell.  ShowANIM is freely distributable so you can
            include it with pictures and/or animations you have created.
@node

@node G_SHOW "IFF FORM SHO1 file format"
  IFF FORM SHO1 file format
    This is the format used in Presentation Master for the show files.
    This format is currently not available outside of Oxxi Inc. as it
    is so closely tied to internal structures within Presentation
    Master.  This may be reconsidered as needs develop for others
    to have the file format.  Contact Oxxi Inc. if you feel you have
    a legitimate reason for details on this format.
@endnode

@node G_Spline
 Spline -
 Drawing curves in Presentation Master always creates splines.  A
 spline consists of two or more points, through which is passed
 a smooth curve, with continuous derivatives at each node (point).
 Presentation Master will convert a spline to a series of 4-point
 @{" beziers " link G_Bezier} prior to rendering the curve, but the user sees only the
 points which define the path through which the curve is to pass.
 Adjusting the positions of the points is a simple matter, but
 may not be sufficient at times to get a curve which is exactly
 what the user wants.  In these cases, the spline can be selected,
 in the same way as it is selected for editing, and the
 @{" convert to bezier " link EP_Convert} tool can be used to change the spline into
 a series of 4-pt beziers for more detailed editing.

 Due to internal limitations, a spline is limited to about 30
 consecutive points.  When entering a spline, if the limit is
 reached, then a "corner" point is put in next to split the
 spline into two, or more, spline segments.  If the user isn't
 satisfied with the appearance, then the entire sequence can
 be converted to beziers and the offending points forced to be
 smooth by adjusting the bezier control points.

 A closed spline will sometimes be generated when an object connects
 the last point back to the start, and the entire object is a
 curve.  This will assure that the connection back to the start
 point will be a continuous slope.  This only happens when there
 are 30 or less points in the spline.
@endnode

@node G_Template "Slide Template and Template Family"
 Template - This is a special show consisting of slides which form
            templates for the creation of new slides.  These provide
            the background graphics as well as the types and numbers of
            content layers (text, graphics, title, and image layers) and
            the attributes for these layers like fonts, colors, etc.
@endnode

@node G_TextLayer "Text Layer"
 Text Layer - One of the layer types which make up the content of the
              slide.  This layer type consists of text which can be entered
              directly or imported and can have any number of indention
              levels, the first three of which can have unique fonts, sizes,
              styles, colors, etc.
@endnode

@node G_Thumbnail Thumbnails
  Thumbnails - These are the miniature slide images which are
               maintained by Presentation Master for all slides, and
               are used to represent the slide on various screens
               including the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.

               For @{" Empty Slides " link G_EmptySlide}, and @{" Black Slides " link G_BlackSlide}, the thumbnail
               is automatic, however for @{" IFF Slides " link ImageSlide} and @{" Layered Slides " link LayeredSlide}
               Presentation Master must create the thumbnail from
               the slide image.  @{" Vulcanized " link G_Vulcanize} files have no thumbnails
               since they are intended for stand-alone slideshows.
               In that case, built-in thumbnails are used if a
               vulcanized show is loaded as a show.
@endnode

@node G_TIFF
 TIFF graphic image format -
   This is a file format (like @{" IFF " link G_IFF} on the Amiga) used on MSDOS machines
   for the storing of graphic images.  This format is applicable to
   Presentation Master in only one regard.  It is the format used in
   @{" EPSF " link G_EPS} @{" ClipArt " link ClipArt} for the @{" preview " link FR_Preview} image.  Thus, TIFF images are both
   read (in the @{" file requester " link FileReq} when doing a preview) and written (in
   the @{" Export_EPS module " link ExportEPS} when saving an EPSF file).
@endnode

@node G_Vulcanize Vulcanize
  Vulcanize - Vulcanization is a term in Presentation Master which
          refers to the process of "hardening" a presentation so as
          to be transportable.  In particular, all @{" layered slides " link LayeredSlide}
          are converted to @{" IFF slides " link ImageSlide} and a new show file is created
          which is missing much of the normal content of a show file
          (such as the @{" thumbnails " link G_Thumbnail}).  This Vulcanized show can be
          shown with @{" PMshow " link PMshow}, the freely distributable player program
          which accompanies Presentation Master.

          Another big advantage to vulcanizing a show is the fact that
          many layered slides can often be quite time-consuming to
          draw.  Particularly if there is a lot of structured clipart
          involved.  A vulcanized show only has to pop in the IFF file
          of the slide, which is normally much faster.  However, if you
          have turned on narration and let the narrator just read the
          text layers on your slide, this will no longer function on
          the vulcanized show since text layers are part of the layered
          slide, and not the IFF slide.  To get around this, enter the
          text to be narrated in the narration text window.
@endnode

@node G_Toolkit "Toolkit/Palette/ToolPalette"
 Toolkit, Palette, ToolPalette
   These are synonyms for the tool palettes used in various places
   in Presentation Master.
   Palette can also refer to the color palette.
@endnode

@node G_Transition "Slide Transition"
 Transition - The manner in which slideshow will change from one slide
              to another.
@endnode

@node G_Transparent "Transparent objects/colors"
 Transparent - One can select transparent colors for filled objects which
               are the colors with the letter "T" showing through the
               color in the color palette.  These are in reality dither
               patterns of the solid color which let the background show
               through the checkerboard pattern.  If the background color
               is also dithered, then strange patterns can sometimes
               develop and/or only one of the background dither colors will
               show through.
               N.B. that PostScript cannot represent transparency, so
               transparent colors will NOT appear transparent in PostScript.
               Instead, they will be rendered as a 50% mix of color 0 and
               the transparent color (Hey! do you have a better idea?).
@endnode

@node G_Trashcan "Trash can in slide sorter screen"
 Trashcan - This is an icon in the slidesorter screen which can be used
            for disposing of a slide, including all child slides, by
            simply dragging the slide to the trashcan.  The last item
            placed in the trashcan may be retained for awhile so one can
            retrieve it by simply clicking on the trashcan and dragging
            the slide back out to some other placement.  N.B. that this
            retrieval may not last too long, especially if you are short
            of ram, and this is definitely not recommended as a storage
            location for working slides.  You may change the trashcan
            icon to that of a @{" black hole " link G_BlackHole} by pressing shift-help while in
            the slidesorter screen.
@endnode

@node G_TTFN "T.T.F.N."
 T.T.F.N. - TaTaForNow - taken from Winnie the Pooh.  This message is used
            on virtually all programs written by this author upon exit,
            except this one.  It was deemed non-professional by those who
            had a say in the product direction.
@endnode

@node G_UnGroup "UnGroup objects"
 UnGroup - This is the action of splitting a compound object into its
           individual subobjects.  Many objects are pre-grouped, such
           as bar and pie charts and polytext strings and clipart.  Also
           one may group any objects desired for treating them as a
           single unit.  Ungrouping will break up these objects again.
           Note that some objects have information attached to the group
           which will be lost if the object is ungrouped.  This includes
           objects like charts, polytext, etc., where information about
           how the object was created is attached to the topmost
           grouping.  Ungrouping at this level destroys this information
           so one cannot return to the chart module, or wherever it was
           created, to modify and re-create it.  Note that an alternative
           to ungrouping is to use the tools in the edit tool palette to
           drop down a level in the heirarchy of the object.  In that
           way you can work on subobjects without having to ungroup the
           object itself.
@endnode

@node G_Zoom "Zoom"
 Zoom - This permits viewing a small portion of the graphics close-up.
        It also permits a wide angle view where the entire slide is
        rendered in miniature in the middle of the screen which permits
        working on graphics which extend beyond the boundaries of
        the screen.  See the @{" Zoom " link HP_Zoom} tool for more details.
@endnode

@node PMprefs "Presentation Master Preferences Program"
Presentation Master Preferences Program

 PMprefs is a master preferences program for Presentation Master.  It
 provides a graphical interface to modifying the @{" s:.PM.settings " link PMsettings} file
 which was originally created in the installation process.  This file
 contains things like default disk paths, @{" PostScript " link PostScript} font equivalencing
 (so the PostScript module will know what PostScript fonts to request
 for various @{" Amiga fonts " link BitmapFonts} used in the slides), and basic things like
 the initial program mode (Slide Sorter screen, or a single slide),
 etc.

 Normal installation makes PMprefs available via an icon in the main
 installation drawer for Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node PMsettings "Master Settings for Presentation Master"
Master Settings for Presentation Master

 The installation procedure for Presentation Master places a file
 named ".PM.settings" into the s: directory.  This is always loaded
 by Presentation Master upon execution, and also many modules will
 also load the file.  This file contains various default information
 for the program and also things like @{" PostScript " link PostScript} font names to be
 used for various @{" Amiga fonts " link BitmapFonts}.  This file is ASCII and may be
 examined and edited with a common text editor, but there is a
 preferences file, called @{" PMprefs " link PMprefs} which is specifically
 provided for this purpose.
@endnode

@node PMshow "Stand-Alone Slideshow Program"
Stand-Alone Slideshow Program

 PMshow is a freely distributable slideshow program which you can use
 to distribute your shows to others.  PMshow only shows @{" Vulcanized " link G_Vulcanize}
 shows, which is suitable since they do not require all the fonts,
 backdrops, templates, etc., which are necessary to load and work on
 a full show.

 The procedure is to vulcanize your show, usually to one or more
 floppy disks.  Then copy PMshow to the last disk, upon which the
 show file with its icon are stored.  Make sure the icon has PMshow
 as the default tool.  Then these floppies can be given to anyone
 and they can view your final show.

 Normal installation makes PMshow available via an icon in the main
 installation drawer for Presentation Master.  From there you can drag
 it onto any floppy of interest.
@endnode

@node ERROR1
 Normally, when a popup menu cannot be opened, it is due to low ram.  The
 popup menus require a bit of chip ram for proper operation.
@endnode

@node ERROR2
 You may have an incorrect show module selected - check the SlideShow menu
 item in the project menu in the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.  Also, the show
 module may not exist on your disk or may not be in the path indicated
 by the module path specifications.  Use @{" PMprefs " link PMprefs} program to check the
 module paths and then see if the @{" slideshow " link Slideshow} module is in that path.
@endnode

@node ERROR3
 In an OPEN situation, the filename you specify MUST be an existing file.
 The only other alternative is to "Cancel" from the file requester.
@endnode

@node ERROR4
 In a SAVE situation, you are warned when the file you specify to save
 to already exists, since you may not intend to overwrite anything.
@endnode

@node ERROR5
 When morphing objects, the two objects MUST match on a point-by-point
 basis.  The easiest way to accomplish this is to make one object, and
 then clone it and alter the clone in any way desired.  The morph will
 then simply linearly interpolate each point between the two selected
 objects.  N.B. that if one of the objects has a point deleted, or added,
 or is converted from spline to beziers, etc., then the two objects will
 not be identical!
@endnode

@node ERROR6
 Upon trying to open a window, the system may fail due to a variety of
 reasons.  The most common one is lack of sufficient chip ram.
 Presentation Master will attempt to gain additional ram in several
 ways (such as emptying the trashcan), however, the user can help by
 flipping back to the workbench or CLI (use Amiga-N and Amiga-M to
 do this) and terminate any other programs which may be utilizing
 chip ram.  If none exist which can help, then you may have to terminate
 execution and seek other means such as a re-boot.  Sometimes there
 may be sufficient ram, but not enough in contiguous blocks.
@endnode

@node ERROR7
 You cannot paste anything if you havn't cut/copied something to the
 paste buffer.  The paste buffer can also be loaded by importing an
 ascii file.
@endnode

@node ERROR8
 Anytime you delete a layer from a slide, the contents of that layer
 will be lost.  If you wish to move the contents to another layer,
 first cut/paste between layers or slides before deleteing the layer.
@endnode

@node ERROR9
 This operation loads the color palette with the colors on the last
 color font opened.  In this case, no color font has been opened, so
 there is no such color palette.
@endnode

@node ERROR10
 In order to combine objects, the objects MUST be subobjects of the
 selected object group, and none of them may in turn have subobjects.
@endnode

@node ERROR11
 In order to combine objects, all the subobjects MUST be DRAW type
 objects.  There cannot be any TEXT objects present.
@endnode

@node ERROR12
 This is an internal sanity-check error - Please notify Oxxi of
 the circumstances.
@endnode

@node ERROR13
 You have to load in a color palette for editing.  This can be done
 by selecting one of the standard or user palettes or the palette can
 be extracted from a selected layered slide.
@endnode

@node ERROR14
 You can currently only extract a color palette from a layered slide.
@endnode

@node ERROR15
 You can currently only store the color palette to a layered slide.
@endnode

@node ERROR16
 The information regarding the creation of this object (in, for example,
 a chart module) is held on the top grouping of the object.  If you
 ungroup it at this level, this information will be lost.  The object
 will still be the same, but you will lose the capability of returning
 to the creation module to revise the original data upon which this
 object is based.
@endnode

@node ERROR17
 Any time you change the color of an object with subobjects, you will
 change the color of ALL subobjects, which may destroy the identity of
 the object.  For instance, if the object is a pie chart, all pie
 segments will turn to the new color.  If the object is a piece of
 clipart, all parts will be made the same color.  This action may be
 undesirable in many cases.
@endnode

@node ERROR18
 This is a problem in invocation of the slide sorter window.  There isn't
 enough ram to hold the minislide images, or other relevant information.
@endnode

@node ERROR19
 Loading a file in BRIEF is much faster and requires much less memory
 than loading it in FULL.  However, some other operations are slowed down
 since Presentation Master may have to reference the disk file for the
 data for a slide.
@endnode

@node ERROR20
 This will change the color palette on all templates in the template family
 currently loaded into memory.  This will NOT alter the disk file for
 the template family unless you save the template back out to disk.
@endnode

@node ERROR21
 Template matching is based on the name on the template (i.e. "Text1",
 "Title1", etc.).  If the new template family fails to have a template
 with the same name as the template on the slide, then Presentation
 Master doen't know what template to substitute.
@endnode

@node ERROR22
 When there are more than one object on the layer which were created
 by the Chart module, then Presentation Master doen't know which one
 you wish to work on when you click on the chart tool.  To work on
 one, you must select it with the select tool, and then use the 'E'
 tool on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} to edit that chart (in which case you
 will be returned to the Chart module to re-make the chart).
@endnode

@node ERROR23
 Changing the backdrop will alter the backdrop on all templates in this
 template family.  This, in and of itself, will not alter the @{" thumbnails " link G_Thumbnail}.
@endnode

@node ERROR24
 This will loop through all templates in this family, rendering each one
 in turn, and saving a new @{" thumbnail " link G_Thumbnail} of each one to the template family.
@endnode

@node ERROR25
 Changing the pagesize will alter the page size on all templates in this
 template family.  This, in and of itself, will not alter the
 @{" thumbnails " link G_Thumbnail".
@endnode

@node ERROR26
 Presentation Master loads a master settings file from the s: directory
 called @{" .PM.settings " link PMsettings}.  This file has all sorts of vital information
 to the proper running of the program, including PostScript font
 equivalencing, paths to where the external modules are stored, etc.
 This file is normally created during the installation procedure.
 If it is missing then check to see if, due to multiple disk partitions,
 it may be on another s directory somewhere (what was the situation
 when you installed the program?).  If it cannot be found then use the
 installation procedure.  Answer questions regarding where things are
 to be found, but don't allow any actual installation to occur (run in
 EXPERT mode to have this level of control!) and a new .PM.settings file
 will be created for you.
@endnode

@node PaintToolPalette "Tool Palette for Paint"
The paint tools, in approximate arrangement, are as follows:

 @{" Line Segments              " link HP_Line  }    @{" Text Entry                 " link HP_Text}
 @{" Multipoint Straight Lines  " link HP_Lines }    @{" Multipoint Spline          " link HP_Spline}
 @{" Closed Polygon             " link HP_Poly  }    @{" Closed Spline              " link HP_PSpline}
 @{" Regular CLosed Polygon     " link HP_RPoly }    @{" Regular Closed Spline      " link HP_RSpline}
 @{" Rectangles                 " link HP_Rect  }    @{" Ellipses                   " link HP_Ellipse}
 @{" Rounded Rects              " link HP_RRect }    @{" Create/Edit Bar/Pie Chart  " link HP_Chart}
 @{" Zoom/Wide-Angle(Shifted)   " link HP_Zoom  }    @{" Snap to Grid               " link HP_Gridsnap}
 @{" Limited Undo               " link HP_Undo  }    @{" Snapshot for Undo          " link HP_Snapshot}
 @{" Redraw Paint Layer         " link HP_Redraw}    @{" Clear Paint Layer          " link HP_Clear}
                 @{" Current Draw Color (PopUp) " link HP_Color}
 @{" Pick Edit Object           " link HP_Pick  }    @{" Return from Paint          " link HP_Return}

This is the base Tool Palette used for the object based paint
system in Presentation Master.  This palette is primarily for
the creation (drawing) of objects.  To alter an object one
needs to select it and edit it via the @{" Edit Tool Palette " link EditToolPalette}.
@endnode

@node HP_Line "Line Segment tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool allows one to drag out single line segments by positioning
 the cursor to one end, pressing the left mouse button down, moving the
 cursor to the other end, and releasing the mouse button.

 If the shift key is held down during the drag, the line will be
 constrained to horizontal or vertical.

 If you do a shift-click on the tool, a @{" settings window " link ObjectStyle} for paint objects
 will appear allowing you to specify things like line width.
@endnode

@node HP_Text "Text Entry tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 Once you click on this tool, you then click on the screen and a
 cross-hair guide will appear.  Then you simply enter text from the
 keyboard.  If you click somewhere on the screen, the cross-hair will
 move to that point.  When done, click the RIGHT mouse button to
 terminate text entry.  While entering text, the text is displayed
 in complement mode without full styling.  When text entry is
 terminated, the text is re-rendered in proper color and style.

 A Shift-click on the tool will produce a @{" text settings " link TextStyle} window which
 permits you to set such things as font, size, color, bullet, etc.

 Text entry can utilize TABs for indention, in which case there are
 three separate font, size, color, etc., specifications for no indent,
 single indent, and multiple-TAB indents.  This is similar to the
 text entry in text layers.

 Text may be entered left aligned, centered, or right aligned, according
 to the setting in the settings window.
@endnode

@node HP_Lines "Multipoint Straight Lines tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 To use this tool, you first select it by clicking on it.  Then as you
 click on points on the screen, lines will be drawn point-to-point.
 The only difference between this tool and the one to the right, is
 that the one to the right draws curves.  If you hold the CTRL key down
 when clicking on a point, this tool will draw curves, which permits
 generating interspersed lines and curves with the same tool.
 The curves drawn are @{" splines " link G_Spline} and only show up as curves if three or
 more points are drawn, in which case a smooth curve will be passed
 through the points provided the middle points were "curve" points.

 Clicking the right button will terminate the sequence and redraw the
 lines in the correct color and style.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, etc.
@endnode

@node HP_Spline "Multipoint Spline tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 To use this tool, you first select it by clicking on it.  Then as you
 click on points on the screen, curves will be drawn point-to-point.
 The only difference between this tool and the one to the left, is
 that the one to the left draws lines.  If you hold the CTRL key down
 when clicking on a point, this tool will draw lines, which permits
 generating interspersed lines and curves with the same tool.
 The curves drawn are @{" splines " link G_Spline} and only show up as curves if three or
 more points are drawn, in which case a smooth curve will be passed
 through the points.

 Clicking the right button will terminate the sequence and redraw the
 lines in the correct color and style.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, etc.
@endnode

@node HP_Poly "Closed Polygon tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 To use this tool, you first select it by clicking on it.  Then as you
 click on points on the screen, lines will be drawn point-to-point.
 The only difference between this tool and the one to the right, is
 that the one to the right draws curves.  If you hold the CTRL key down
 when clicking on a point, this tool will draw curves, which permits
 generating interspersed lines and curves with the same tool.
 The curves drawn are @{" splines " link G_Spline} and only show up as curves if three or
 more points are drawn, in which case a smooth curve will be passed
 through the points provided the middle points were "curve" points.

 Clicking the right button will terminate the sequence and redraw the
 object in the correct color and style.  The last point will be connected
 back to the starting point and the object will be open (lines) or
 filled according to if you clicked on the left or right side of the
 tool to start with.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, etc.
@endnode

@node HP_PSpline "Closed Spline tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 To use this tool, you first select it by clicking on it.  Then as you
 click on points on the screen, curves will be drawn point-to-point.
 The only difference between this tool and the one to the left, is
 that the one to the left draws lines.  If you hold the CTRL key down
 when clicking on a point, this tool will draw lines, which permits
 generating interspersed lines and curves with the same tool.
 The curves drawn are @{" splines " link G_Spline} and only show up as curves if three or
 more points are drawn, in which case a smooth curve will be passed
 through the points.

 Clicking the right button will terminate the sequence and redraw the
 object in the correct color and style.  The last point will be connected
 back to the starting point and the object will be open (lines) or
 filled according to if you clicked on the left or right side of the
 tool to start with.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, etc.
@endnode

@node HP_RPoly "Regular Closed Polygon tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will draw regular closed polygons, either open or filled.
 This means an object drawn with a specified number of sides, of equal
 length, inscribed within an ellipse or circle.  Actually, the sides
 will not be equal length if it is in an ellipse, but will be connected
 between equally spaced points about a circle, which will be stretched
 to fit the ellipse.  The default is for four sides which produces a
 diamond.  However, a shift-click on the tool will produce the
 @{" object style window " link ObjectStyle} which has provisions for specifying the number
 of slides.  Three produce a triangle, 5 a pentagon, etc.  There is
 also provision for the number of rotations, or the angle between
 sides.  If you select 5 sides and two rotations, this tool will
 produce a 5-pointed star.  Experiment to see what it will do.
@endnode

@node HP_RSpline "Regular Closed Spline tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This is identical to the tool to the left, the @{" closed polygon tool " link HP_RPoly},
 except instead of the sides being lines, a closed @{" spline " link G_Spline} will be passed
 through all the sides of the polygon.  This will normally just produce
 an approximation to a circle or ellipse, however if you make the
 number of rotations larger than one (as you do for a 5-pointed star)
 then you will get some interesting rosettes and other designs.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, number of sides,
 number of rotations, etc.
@endnode

@node HP_Rect "Rectangle/Square tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This is the normal tool found in most paint and draw programs which
 produces rectangles or squares (hold the shift key down to constrain
 to a square).  To use it, click on the tool, and then move the cursor
 to a point on the screen where you want one corner of the square and
 press down the left mouse button.  Then, with the button depressed,
 move the cursor to the opposite corner of the desired rectangle or
 square (you will see a complement drawn rectangle) and then release
 the button.  Upon releasing the button, the object will be redrawn in
 the proper color, style, etc.  It will be either open or filled
 according to which side of the tool you clicked on originally.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, etc.  Note that
 the filled rectangle tool is the only tool, at present, which can
 be styled with gradations.  These gradations are specified in this
 style window.
@endnode

@node HP_Ellipse "Ellipse/Circle tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This is like the traditional ellipse and circle tools found in all
 paint and draw programs.  To use it you first click on the tool.  Then
 you move the cursor to where you want the center of the object, and
 press down the left mouse button.  Then drag the cursor outward and
 an ellipse will be drawn in complement mode.  If you press down a
 shift key, the ellipse will be constrained to a circle.  When it is
 the correct size, release the mouse button, at which point it will
 be redrawn in the correct color and style.  It will be open or
 filled according to what side of the tool you clicked on to begin
 with.

 Ellipses in Presentation Master are drawn as 12-point splines.  This
 object can be edited and converted to beziers if you wish.  A simple
 operation is to convert it to beziers and then edit the points.  If
 you just grab one of the bezier anchor points and drag it away from
 the ellipse, it makes a point much like the balloons for text in
 cartoon strips.

 A Shift-click on this tool will invoke the @{" style window " link ObjectStyle} for selection
 of things like line width, color, shadowing, embossing, etc.
@endnode

@node HP_RRect "Rounded Rectangle tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This is exactly like the @{" plain rectangle tool " link HP_Rect} except that the corners
 are rounded.  The radius of the corner is controlled in the
 @{" style window " link ObjectStyle}.  These corners are implemented as @{" beziers " link G_Bezier} which the
 user can edit if he wishes.
@endnode

@node HP_Chart "Create/Edit Bar/Pie Chart tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool invokes the chart creation module.  If there is no chart
 present on this layer, then the Chart module will assume you wish
 to create one.  If one exists then it will be modified by the
 Chart module and the revised one will replace the one previously
 there (unless you 'cancel' out of the Chart module).

 If multiple charts exist on this layer, then this tool will NOT
 invoke the Chart module at all.  In this case you must select
 the chart, as if for edit, and then use the 'E' tool in the
 edit tool palette to edit it, which just invokes the Chart module
 for the selected chart.

 The creation of multiple charts on one layer is a rather advanced
 operation.  It can only be achieved by invoking the Chart module
 from the Create menu in paint, since this will invoke the module
 for creation of a new chart even in a chart already exists.
@endnode

@node HP_Zoom "Zoom/Wide-Angle tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 To zoom in, you click on this tool and then drag a rectangle around
 the area you wish to zoom into.  The rectangle you drag out will be
 roughly full-screen after the zoom.  Note that there is a roughly
 30x limitation to the zoom.

 To go wide-angle on the slide, you do a shift-click on this tool and
 then drag out a rectangle on the screen.  The rectangle is the rough
 size you wish to see the ENTIRE slide drawn.

 N.B. that when you zoom either in or out, text will not be drawn
 but will be represented by a rectangle on the screen with an 'X'
 drawn through it.  The main intent of zoom is to permit detailed
 work on drawn objects, or to zoom out and then make objects large
 and drag them partially, or entirely, out of the slide.  This is
 very useful for some animation generation.

 There are several keyboard shortcuts and helps provided in zoom:
    Amiga-1:    Returns to normal size.
    Amiga-2:    Zoom in x2
    Amiga-3:    Zoom out x2
    Cursor Keys (up,down,left,right arrow keys):  Pans the zoomed
                image around in the indicated direction.  Normal
                panning is 1/5 of a screen at a time.  Hold the shift
                key down for a faster pan (1/2 screen at a time) or
                the CTRL key down for a full screen at a time.
                N.B. that this can be slow since the screen will be
                completely redrawn at each step.  It may be faster
                to go back to normal size and re-zoom to a new location.
@endnode

@node HP_Gridsnap "Snap to Grid tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will toggle gridsnap and guide lines on and off.  The
 frequency and appearance of the snap points and the guide lines
 are controlled in the @{" gridsnap window " link GridsnapPanel} which is invoked by a
 shift-click on this tool.
@endnode

@node GridsnapPanel "Grid Snap Control Panel"
 This window permits selection of what is to appear when gridsnap is
 toggled on.  You can select grid display or guidelines and you can
 select various sizes for both the grid display and the gridsnap grid.
 N.B. that the gridsnap does not generally match the displayed grid,
 but it can if desired.  Normally gridsnap is much finer than is
 practical to display on-screen.
@endnode

@node HP_Undo "Limited Undo tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This is an undo tool, except what it really does is restore the
 objects to the state at the last @{" snapshot " link HP_Snapshot}.  Snapshots may be done
 manually or automatically.

 A second use for this tool is that if you are entering line segments,
 this will remove the last line point drawn.  This works for the line
 segment tools and the open/filled polygon tools.
@endnode

@node HP_Snapshot "Snapshot (for Undo) tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is used to snapshot the current object configuration for
 a pending future undo operation.  If you want to experiment with
 a tool, for instance, a snapshot beforehand will permit undoing
 the entire operation if you don't like it.  Keep in mind that you
 may have auto-snapshot turned on which may override your snapshot
 at some point, and also there is an auto-snapshot at various times
 in any case, such as when you select an object for editing or go to
 create a bar chart.
@endnode

@node HP_Redraw "Redraw tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This simply redraws the screen.  This isn't often necessary, but
 can be helpful at times.
@endnode

@node HP_Clear "Clear tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will first of all verify with you that you want to do
 this, and then if so it will delete all objects from the current
 paint layer.  Note that they are really placed into the undo
 buffer so you can still bring them back in if you wish.
@endnode

@node HP_Color "Current Draw Color (PopUp) for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 When you click on this tool, a popup 256 color palette appears for
 selection of the current draw @{" color " link Colors}.  Only the first 16 are suitable
 for text, but the entire set is available for drawn objects.

 When you do a shift-click on this tool, the @{" color edit window " link ColorEditWindow} for the
 base 16 colors is presented.

 When you do a ALT-click on this tool, the @{" process color window " link ProcessColors}
 will be invoked.
@endnode

@node HP_Pick "Object Edit Selection tool for paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 In order to alter an object, you select this tool and them move the
 cursor around the screen.  When over a given object, a rectangle will
 appear around that object with moving dashes on it.  If you click the
 mouse button at that time, that object will be selected for editing.
 At that time a new Edit Tool Palette will appear.

 The dashes which move on the rectangle have two patterns depending
 on the makeup of the object.  If they are simple dashes moving
 along the boundary from the upper left corner to the lower right,
 then the object is a simple, single, object.  If the object is
 a grouping of subobjects, then the dashes appear to undulate and
 not really move along the line.
@endnode

@node HP_Return "Return from Paint tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" tool palette " link PaintToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool "returns" from paint back to the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.

 Usually, upon return the slide will be re-rendered and a new @{" thumbnail " link Thumbnail}
 will be generated.  This process can be sped up in one of two ways:
  * Shift-click will NOT re-render, but will make the thumbnail
    from the slide image as-is.  This includes names of layers and
    other extra items rendered on the screen.
  * Alt-click will Not re-render and ALSO will NOT remake the thumbnail.
    The thumbnail will remain as-is.  This is very handy when you arn't
    done with the slide anyway, or if you havn't made any noticable
    changes to it.
@endnode

@node EditToolPalette "Tool Palette for Editing Paint Objects"
The edit tools, in approximate arrangement, are as follows:

 @{" Resize Object              " link EP_Resize }    @{" Rotate Object              " link EP_Rotate}
 @{" Process/Output Object      " link EP_Process}    @{" Object Style               " link EP_Style}
                 @{" Main Object Color (PopUp)  " link EP_Color}
 @{" Edit Object                " link EP_Edit   }    @{" Convert to Beziers         " link EP_Convert}
 @{" Object Alignment           " link EP_Align  }    @{" Toggle Fill of Object      " link EP_Fill}
 @{" Group Objects              " link EP_Group  }    @{" Ungroup Objects            " link EP_Ungroup}
 @{" Combine Sub-Object         " link EP_Combine}    @{" Burst into Subobjects      " link EP_Burst}
 @{" Cut/Copy Object            " link EP_Cut    }    @{" Paste Object               " link EP_Paste}
 @{" Pull Object to Front       " link EP_Pull   }    @{" Push Object to Rear        " link EP_Push}
 @{" go to Parent Object        " link EP_Parent }    @{" Select Child Object        " link EP_Child}
 @{" Pick New Edit Object       " link EP_Pick   }    @{" Return to Paint            " link EP_Return}
@endnode

@node EP_Resize "Resize Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 Actually, since resize is the default mode in editing, this tool
 is somewhat unnecessary.  In resizing, a box is placed around an
 object with nine grab points:
    Grab a corner to resize by moving the two sides connected to
    the grab point.  If the Shift key is held down, then aspect
    ratio is maintained.  If the Alt key is held down, then the
    entire rectangle is resized around the center.

    Grab a side to move that side in/out.

    Grab the center to move the object to a different position.

 From the menu is a slight variation on this tool called "Kern Object".
 Kern is identical to resize, except that subobjects are NOT resized,
 only their position is altered.  Thus if you have a grouping of
 objects, like characters of outline text generated by the polytext
 or bullet creation tools, then this will allow moving the objects
 farther apart, or closer together.
@endnode

@node EP_Rotate "Rotate Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool puts up a slight variation to the normal rectangle with
 grab points.  Also there is a "V" across the rectangle so you will
 always know which way the original orientation is.

 Grab a corner and rotate it about the center for rotation.

 Grab the center to move the object as a whole to a new location.
@endnode

@node EP_Process "Process/Output Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This is one of the most powerful tools available in editing of
 objects.  This is a gateway to a host of object manipulation
 modules.  The shipping version of Presentation Master includes
 three such modules:

    @{" Distort Object      " link DistortModule}
    @{" Bend Object         " link BendModule}
    @{" Fit Object to Circle" link FitToCircleModule}

 Other modules are in preparation including one to output the
 selected object as an Adobe Illustrator format @{" EPS file " link ExportEPS}.
@endnode

@node DistortModule - "Object Distortion Module"
Distort
   This permits the user to distort a four sided
   box around the object in any way that pleases him, even
   creating an hourglass shape (or bow tie).  This is done
   by grabbing the corner and/or side grab points and moving
   them about.  Then the small tool palette can be used to
   remap the object to that new shape in eithere 2D or
   perspective.  Perspective is identical to 2D except that
   perspective foreshortening is applied on the assumption
   that the reason that two opposite sides are of different
   length is due to one being further away than the other.
   This permits accurate 3D renderings, so long as the box
   is distorted to look like a rectangle in 3D.  Obviously
   you can do all sorts of wierd things if you wish.  There
   is a cancel and a restore button to undo anything you do
   prior to leaving the module.  Once you click on OK, the
   changes are done permanently (except for using UnDo back
   on the paint palette).
@endnode

@node BendModule - "Object Bending Module"
Bend
   This permits the user to distort an object to a
   bent outline.  This is a simple bend module, a more
   extensive one is planned for future release.  The top
   and bottom of the enclosing rectangle consist of 4-point
   beziers and the user can bend the box in various ways by
   adjusting the anchor and/or control points.  The shift
   key will move two or more points in unison.  Experiment
   with it!  The cancel and restore buttons permit undoing
   any unsuccessful experimentation.

   N.B. that items with straight lines, like rectangles, will
   not bend well, if at all.  A future version of this
   module will handle this, but for now, only objects with
   small frequent line segments will bend well (like outline
   text).
@endnode

@node FitToCircleModule "Fit-To-Circle Module"
Fit to Circle
   This permits the user to specify a circular
   arc to use in remapping the object.  Grab points allow the
   moving of the four sides of the arc-shaped area.  Shift
   key will move pairs of sides together.

   Hints:  If, for example, you wish to have several lines
   of polytext in concentric circles, do not move the center
   of the circle.  Use this module for each one, moving the
   four sides of the arc, but leaving the center alone so
   they will all be centered about the same circle.  Then,
   when all are finished, group all the lines of text
   together and move and/or resize the group together to
   the final size and location.

   The "Invert" tool does not cause immediate changing, but
   will make the next remapping be inverted.

   The "Render 3D" capability will cause perspective
   foreshortening towards the center of the circle, much
   like as if the text were on the inside of a cylinder.

   Note that when used with outline text (generated by either
   the polytext or bullet modules) the text is not simply
   tilted and positioned around a circle, like other
   draw programs.  The text is actually distorted to fit
   the wedge portion of the arc shape.  Thus, for instance,
   the letter 'H' will have its sides along radii to the
   circle!
@endnode

@node ExportEPS "Export EPS module"
Export_EPS
 The Export_EPS module will be available on an expansion pak for
 Presentation Master and will allow the saving of any graphic image
 as an @{" EPSF " link G_EPSF} file, complete with a TIFF preview image.

 When installed, it will appear on the popup menu for remapping an
 object (like Distort, Bend, and Fit-To-Circle) since it basically
 has to have a single object to act upon.  To use it, simply select
 the object desired (group several objects together if necessary)
 and click on the object remap tool in the object edit tool palette.
 Then select the Export_EPS module from the popup menu.  You will
 have a choice of three preview images: none, @{" EPSI " link EPSI}, and @{" EPSF " link G_EPSF}.  EPSF
 is the one that is compatible with Presentation Master import and
 it will generate a PC compatible EPSF file much like the ones you
 got as samples or may purchase from commercial clipart companies.
 EPSF files may be easily imported to other programs and the preview
 image will normally be recognized.  EPSI is a newer "Interchange"
 format which seems to primarily be used on UNIX systems.  The
 preview is contained in ASCII within the comments of the file and
 will probably not be used by many, if any, Amiga programs.  EPSI
 preview is NOT used by Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node EP_Style "Object Style"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool invokes an object style window.  If the object is a single
 text object, then the @{" text style " link TextStyle} window is invoked so you can alter
 the font, size, color, style, etc., of the text.  Otherwise the
 @{" object style " link ObjectStyle} panel is invoked so color, style, etc., of a drawn object
 can be altered.
@endnode

@node EP_Color "Main Object Color (PopUp)"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This will change the primary color of the selected object to
 the color selected from the popup color palette.  If the
 object is a grouping of subobjects, then you will be informed
 as to the fact that this will change the colors of ALL subobjects.
 This can be disastrous in the case of things like clipart and
 piecharts where colors of individual objects are unique and
 different.  How would a pie chart look if all slices are the
 same color?
@endnode

@node EP_Edit "Edit Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is only active under one of the following situations:
  1) The selected object is a single object, not a grouping.  In
     which case the object may be of two types:
        Text object - A crosshair will appear on the screen and
                      the text will be displayed in complement just
                      as it was when originally created.  You can
                      add to the text or move the cursor around and
                      edit the existing text.  Clicking on the
                      screen will move the crosshair reference lines
                      to the point you clicked, and the RIGHT mouse
                      button is used to terminate the editing.
        Draw object - The control points that define the object will
                      appear and you can grab any of them and move
                      them about.  If there are beziers, then the
                      control points for each anchor point will be
                      connected to the anchor point with a dashed
                      line.  With beziers, holding the shift key
                      down when grabbing an anchor point will move
                      the control point(s) with the anchor point.
                      Holding the shift key down when grabbing a
                      control point will move the other control
                      point on this anchor point (if any) to mirror
                      the grabbed point so the slopes and
                      curvature of the meeting beziers will match.
                      A CTRL-click on a control point will present
                      a small popup menu to add, delete, clone points.
                      Also it allows changing a spline node to a
                      cusp (corner) and vice-versa.
  2) If the selected object is a grouping, the button is ONLY ACTIVE
     if the object was created by a creation module like the bar chart
     module or the polytext or bullet text modules.  In this case,
     clicking on this tool will invoke the originating module for a
     remake of the object.
@endnode

@node EP_Convert "Convert to Beziers"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will convert the current object to be made up of
 @{" beziers " link G_Bezier}.  If the object contains @{" splines " link Spline}, they will be
 converted to the beziers which are identical to the ones used
 to render the spline.  If there are straight lines, they
 will be converted to beziers where the control points lie
 along the line at 1/3 the distance from each anchor point to
 the other anchor point.  For instance, this tool will convert
 a rectangle to be four beziers which can subsequently be
 edited.
@endnode

@node EP_Aligh "Object Alignment"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will invoke the @{" object alignment window " link Align} for operations
 like aligning the subobjects, morphing, etc.  This tool is only
 active when the selected object is a grouping of subobjects.
@endnode

@node EP_Fill "Toggle Fill of Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is only applicable for certain object types.  It will
 toggle the object between an open and filled object.
@endnode

@node EP_Group "Group Objects"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is used for grouping one or more objects below a common
 object, thereby creating a compound object which can be moved,
 resized, or otherwise manipulated as a unit.

 Use of this tool is to first of all select the first object you
 wish in the grouping.  Then click on this tool.  Then move the
 cursor around the screen, selecting any additional objects you
 wish to include in the grouping, and in the order desired.
 Finally, click the RIGHT mouse button to conclude the operation.
@endnode

@node EP_Ungroup "Ungroup Objects"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is only active when the selected object is a grouping
 of subobjects.  Selecting this tool will ungroup the objects at
 which point you must move the cursor over these objects and
 select one for the new current object.
@endnode

@node EP_Combine "Combine Sub-Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool only works when you have a grouping of two or more
 drawn outlines.  Then this will combine them into one drawn
 object.  For example, if you have two concentric, but different
 size, circles.  Combining them will produce a donut shape (or 'O')
 where the center is cut out of the middle.
@endnode

@node EP_Burst "Burst into Subobjects"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This will only work on objects that meet certain requirements.
   1) Objects with multiple paths, such as an outline 'i' where
      the stem and the dot are separate paths, can be divided
      into two objects grouped together.  This permits you to
      make the dot on the 'i' a different color from the stem.
   2) A text object (Amiga text, not outline text) can be burst.
      If the object has multiple lines, it will be burst into
      individual lines.  If not, and if it contains spaces, it
      will be burst into words.  If there are no spaces, then
      it will be burst into individual characters.  Once it is
      burst, the individual items can be changed in color, style,
      font, size, etc.
@endnode

@node EP_Cut "Cut/Copy Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 Clicking on this tool will remove the selected object from
 the layer and place it into the cut/paste buffer so it can
 be pasted in on another layer or slide.  If you didn't
 intend to do this, then just click on the paste tool to
 put it back into the layer.

 A Shift-click on this tool will make a copy of the currently
 selected object and will place that copy into the cut/paste
 buffer, leaving the original object in place.
@endnode

@node EP_Paste "Paste Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is only active if there is an object in the cut/paste
 buffer.  If so, then clicking on this tool will cause that
 object to be added into the current layer, at the current
 grouping level.  Remember, cut/paste works across layers as
 well as across slides and presentations.
@endnode

@node EP_Pull "Pull Object to Front"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 Clicking on his tool will cause the currently selected object
 to be moved to the front of other objects at this grouping
 level.
@endnode

@node EP_Push "Push Object to Rear"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 Clicking on this tool will cause the currently selected object
 to be moved to the rear of other objects at this grouping
 level.
@endnode

@node EP_Parent "go to Parent Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is only active if the currently selected object is
 a subobject (child) of another object.  Selecting this tool
 will automatically make the parent object the current object.
@endnode

@node EP_Child "Select Child Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is only active if the object selected is a grouping of
 subobjects (known as child objects to this parent object).
 Selecting this tool permits you to select one of the child objects
 for editing in the same way that you selected this object in
 the first place.  This permits altering individual objects in
 a grouping, such as an individual bar in a bar chart, without
 having to ungroup the object and destroy the grouping.
@endnode

@node EP_Pick "Pick New Edit Object"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool is like the similar tool on the paint palette which allows
 you to select a new object for editing.
@endnode

@node EP_Return "Return to Paint"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" edit tool palette " link EditToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will return operation back to the @{" paint tool palette " link PaintToolPalette}.
@endnode

@node TextToolPalette "Tool Palette for Text Entry"
The edit tools, in approximate arrangement, are as follows:

 @{" Italicize Selected Text    " link WP_Italic   }    @{" Capitalize Selected Text   " link WP_Cap}
 @{" Make Selected Text Bold    " link WP_Bold     }    @{" Make Selected Text U.Case  " link WP_UC}
 @{" Underline Selected Text    " link WP_Underline}    @{" Make Selected Text L.Case  " link WP_LC}
                 @{" Set Selected Text Color (PopUp)  " link WP_Color}
 @{" Left Justify Text          " link WP_LeftJ    }    @{" Right Justify Text         " link WP_RightJ}
 @{" Center Text                " link WP_Center   }    @{" Invoke Text Settings       " link WP_Settings}
 @{" Redraw Text                " link WP_Redraw   }    @{" Return from Text Entry     " link WP_Return}
@endnode

@node TextSelect "Text Selection in Text Layer"
 To select a block of text, one can do one of the following:
  1) Double click on a word to select that word.
  2) Triple click on a paragraph to select that paragraph.
  3) Drag select the desired text.  This is done by placing the cursor
     at one end of a block of text, pressing the left mouse button,
     dragging the cursor to the other end of the block, and releasing
     the mouse button.  The block of text will now be highlighted.
@endnode

@node WP_Italic "Text Italic Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will toggle the italic mode on a @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text.
 This means that if the text is already italic, it will be made
 non-italic.
@endnode

@node WP_Cap "Text Capitalization Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to be capitalized.  Every character will be made lower case except
 characters that follow a space, which will be made upper case.
@endnode

@node WP_Bold "Text Bold Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will toggle the bold mode on a @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text.
 This means that if the text is already bold, it will be made non-bold.
@endnode

@node WP_UC "Text Upper Case Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to all upper case.
@endnode

@node WP_Underline "Text Underline Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will toggle the underline mode on a @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text.
 This means that if the text is already underlined, it will be made
 non-underlined.

 N.B. that underlining will not be displayed on @{" PostScript " link PostScript} devices
 with the current version of Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node WP_LC "Text Lower Case Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to all lower case.
@endnode

@node WP_LeftJ "Text Left Justify Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to be left aligned.
@endnode

@node WP_RightJ "Text Right Justify Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to be right aligned.
@endnode

@node WP_Center "Text Centering Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to be centered.
@endnode

@node WP_Settings "Text Settings Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will invoke the @{" text settings " link TextStyle} window so you can set things
 like font, size, color, style, bullets, etc.
@endnode

@node WP_Redraw "Text Redraw Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will cause the text in this layer to be redrawn.  This
 is not often required, but there are times where such a cleanup
 is desirable.
@endnode

@node WP_Return "Return From Text Layer"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will return from the text layer to the @{" slide sorter " link SlideSorter} screen.

 Usually, upon return the slide will be re-rendered and a new @{" thumbnail " link Thumbnail}
 will be generated.  This process can be sped up in one of two ways:
  * Shift-click will NOT re-render, but will make the thumbnail
    from the slide image as-is.  This includes names of layers and
    other extra items rendered on the screen.
  * Alt-click will Not re-render and ALSO will NOT remake the thumbnail.
    The thumbnail will remain as-is.  This is very handy when you arn't
    done with the slide anyway, or if you havn't made any noticable
    changes to it.
@endnode

@node WP_Color "Text Color Tool"
 This is one of the tools on the @{" text tool palette " link TextToolPalette} in the paint system.

 This tool will set the @{" selected " link TextSelect} block of text
 to the selected color.  This does NOT effect outline color nor
 shadow color, only the main text color.  This is a popup button
 which will pop up a 16 color palette from which to choose.
 Remember that text must only be one of the base 16 colors in
 the palette in this version of Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node nil
 This help node isn't defined yet...
@endnode

@node CrossDOS
 CrossDOS is a commercial product which can be installed on your
 Amiga for reading and writing MSDOS diskettes.  This product actually
 provides a second name for any of your Amiga disk drives.  When you
 access the drive by this second name (e.g. DI0: instead of DF0:) then
 it is assumed that the drive has an MSDOS diskette in it.  The
 drives change in name from DFn: to DIn: and the product can handle
 both 3.5 inch drives (for 720K MSDOS floppies) as well as the 5.25
 inch drives (for 360K MSDOS floppies).

 A read-only version of CrossDOS is included with Presentation Master
 for use in importing ClipArt on PC diskettes.  You may also wish to
 be able to format and/or write PC diskettes (e.g. for exporting @{" EPS " link G_EPS}
 files to PC diskettes or for outputting @{" PostScript " link PostScript} to floppy for
 sending to @{" service bureaus " link SlideService}) in which case you will have to purchase
 the full CrossDOS product.  See the disk directory for CrossDOS for
 details on how to order the product.
@endnode

@node SlideService "Slide Service Bureaus"
 Slide Service Bureaus -
   Presentation Master can create 35mm slides, and other forms of
   output, via service bureaus through the use of @{" PostScript " link PostScript}.  Currently
   there are printer setup files in the PostScript module for two
   bureaus: @{" Hammond " link Hammond} and @{" CustomColor " link CustomColor}.  These two
   bureaus have been used by Oxxi and each provice excellent quality
   35mm slide output.

   In addition, many other service bureaus can be used, provided they
   accept @{" PostScript " link PostScript} files.  Call Oxxi for more information.
@endnode

@node Hammond "Hammond Photographic Services"

      Hammond Photographic Services
      11280 Washington Place
      Culver City, California 90230
      310) 390-3010

 Hammond specializes in the Amiga and will accept Amiga diskettes
 containing PostScript files.  They also may be able to image
 directly from a Presentation Master SHO1 file provided they have
 all the fonts and other items you may need on their system.
 Call them for more information and pricing.

 Use the Hammond settings file from the PostScript module.
@endnode

@node CustomColor "Custom Color Services"

      Custom Color Services
      1236 South Central Avenue
      Glendale, California 91204
      818) 240-6100
      213) 245-9211

 Custom Color will require PC diskettes or can receive files via
 modem.  They offer a wide variety of formats in addition to 35mm
 slides.  Call for more information and pricing.

 Use the CustomColor settings file from the PostScript module.
@endnode

@node ClipArtSamples "Sample ClipArt"
 Presentation Master includes sample ClipArt EPS images provided by
 eight different commercial ClipArt companies:

    Ad Art from Innovation Advertising & Design
    Click & Clip from Studio Advertising Art
    Cliptures from Dream Maker Software
    Fine Art Impressions from Best Impressions
    Images with Impact! from 3G Graphics Inc.
    LifeART from TechPool Studios
    MapArt from MicroMaps Software
    Totem Graphics

 See the Clip Art booklet for more information on ordering complete
 products from these companies, or for contacting them for more
 information on their product line.  This booklet also contains
 sample images of all the supplied artwork.

 Oxxi would like to thank the above companies for allowing us to
 include their fine artwork with our product.
@endnode

@node Animation "Key Frame Animation Generation"
 The creation of animations in Presentation Master is possible when
 you install the optional @{" Save_ANIM " link SaveANIM} output module.  You can set up
 keyframes in the slide rack and have Presentation Master automatically
 interpolate any objects between the keyframes to produce tweens.
 The number of tweens to PRECEED a slide (to be generated between this
 one and the previous slide) is specified in the settings window for
 this slide (accessed from the slide sorter screen).  The slides MUST
 be identical regarding position and type of layers and the ordering
 and points in the objects.  Tweening simply consists of linear
 interpolation between matching layers and/or object points between
 two slides.  If ANY mismatch in the types, arrangement, or numbers of
 points in corresponding objects/layers in the two slides are detected,
 then the tweening will NOT take place.  The intended way to use this
 feature is to create your base slide with all objects desired.  Then
 clone the slide for as many keyframes as needed (by doing a shift-click
 or a shift-drag of the slide in the slide sorter screen).  Then go to
 any of these keyframes and move and/or distort objects or move or
 resize any layer.  Use the @{" zoom-out " link HP_Zoom} feature to move objects off-screen
 so they can come on-scrren or leave the screen during the animation.
 Then use the Save_ANIM module to record the branch of slides which
 contains the keyframes.  You may have to experiment with various
 numbers of tweens to get the effect you wish.
@endnode

@node SaveANIM "Save_ANIM animation creation module (optional)"
Save_ANIM Module (optional) -
 This module is an output module which will save a slide, a branch of
 slides, or a complete show, to disk as an @{" ANIM " link G_ANIM} animation file.

 Tweening can be used to cause automatic interpolation of objects and/or
 layers which match between pairs of slides.

 The Save_ANIM module will be made available on an expansion pak after
 Presentation Master is released.
@endnode

@node InteractiveOutliner "Interactive Outliner"
 An interactive outliner, similar to some presentation products on other
 platforms, is in preparation.  When it is available, details will be
 announced regarding its availability.  Call Oxxi for more information.
@endnode

@node Fonts
 Presentation Master utilizes several types of fonts, all of which can
 be categorized into two categories:
    @{" Bitmap Fonts  " link BitmapFonts}
    @{" Outline Fonts " link OutlineFonts}
@endnode

@node BitmapFonts
 Bitmap Fonts refers to fonts which are represented in the computer as
 bitmap images of all characters at each size provided.  These fonts are
 used in Presentation Master for general text in text layers and text
 objects in paint.  Indeed, most text used in Presentation Master is
 represented by bitmap fonts due to the speed of rendering quality
 letters.  There are equivalence tables where one may provide names
 of PostScript fonts to use to render various bitmap fonts when output
 is generated in PostScript language format.

 Included with Presentation Master is a collection of bitmap fonts which
 are sufficient to render on-screen all of the normal fonts found on
 low-end PostScript devices.  Due to trademark and other legal restrictions
 Oxxi cannot call these fonts by the traditional names, but they are
 reasonable approximations to the actual font type faces.  The traditional
 names that correspond to each font are as follows:

       Stork          Courier
       Lark           Helvetica
       Finch          Times
       Raven          Palatino
       Swift          Avant Garde
       Swallow        Bookman
       Hawk           New Century Schoolbook
       Flamingo       Zapf Chancery
       Kiwi           Zapf Dingbats
       Dodo           Symbols
@endnode

@node OutlineFonts
 Outline fonts refers to fonts which are algorithmically generated when
 a particular sequence of characters in a particular size is needed.
 These fonts are used to generate objects in the paint system which may
 be edited, distorted, bent, etc, at will.

 Two types of outline fonts are supported by Presentation Master:

   Polygon Fonts - this is a proprietary font format used in VideoTitler
          and Presentation Master.  There are a wide variety of fonts
          available in this format including the ones listed above as
          PostScript font equivalences.  Some are included with
          Presentation Master, others are included with VideoTitler,
          and still more will be made available on expansion paks
          and other means.  These are imported into Presentation Master
          using the PolyText module from the paint system.

   Compugraphic Intellifonts - Otherwise called Bullet fonts, these can
          be used in the same way as polygon fonts by using the
          BulletFont module in Presentation Master.  These fonts are
          available from a wide variety of sources including Agfa
          Compugraphic, Gold Disk, Commodore (with the 2.0 system),
          and others.
@endnode

@node Trouble
  This section has been provided to add stuff as it arises that may be of
  help to users in trouble.  It is NOT all inclusive, and does NOT try to
  duplicate all the stuff that is in the manual in appendices A and B.

  If you cannot resolve your problem through the help here and in the
  manual, then try @{" Tech Support " link TechSupport} at Oxxi.

   Memory problems - One of the main problems in running Presentation
   Master is the amount of memory it requires.  Running on a stock 2Mb
   A3000 is a touchy situation at best.  See the section on memory
   considerations both @{" here " link Memory} and in the manual for suggestions.
   If you have tight memory conditions, at least make sure you are running
   the overlay version of the program and that the OVERLAY command in
   the s:.PM.settings file is set to 3 (e.g. "OVERLAY 3").  Otherwise,
   you might as well forget trying to run on a 2Mb A3000 (unless you have
   installed a 2.0 kickstart ROM).  The best recommendation is to have
   lots of ram on your machine.  If you are running on a PAL Amiga, then
   you might consider forcing Presentation Master into NTSC mode if you
   are running short of ram, and in particular chip ram.  To do this,
   simply edit the s:.PM.settings file and add the command line "NTSC"
   to it.  The screen will be compressed into only 400 lines, but it will
   save a fair amount of ram due the the various buffers required for
   program operation.  PostScript output will not suffer from this.

   Funny Fonts - If menus and some other text come up in a font which does
   not seem to fit properly.  e.g. the keyboard equivalences overlay the
   menu text, or the text seems the wrong size, then you may not have
   Topaz 11 on your system.  Topaz 11 is in the fonts: directory under
   the topaz subdirectory and must be present for Presentation Master to
   look proper, since it is called out for menus and in other places.
   If you are running under 2.0, then topaz 9 will be rescaled by the
   system which makes a font much too wide.  Under 1.3, topaz 9 will be
   used as-is which will also be too wide (but not as much) and will
   be too short.  If size 11 is in the topaz subdirectory in fonts:, but
   you still have the problem, then run the utility "fixfonts" (it comes
   on the 2.0 disks) to make sure it will be recognized by the system.
   Also, if you change anything with topaz, you may have to reboot.

   Cannot grab points - Occasionally Presentation Master will not let you
   grab the grab points in paint for resizing, distorting, etc., an object.
   As much as you try, they do not get "grabbed".  The problem has not yet
   been located, even after a significant amount of effort.  The temporary
   solution is that you have to exit the slide (go to a different slide or
   go back to the slide sorter) and then re-edit the slide.  At that point
   it will be ok.

   When the 256 color popup color palette is invoked, it doesn't go away
   when done.  This is probably due to being so low on memory that there
   wasn't sufficient ram to save the part of the picture covered by the
   popup.  Rather than not putting up the popup, Presentation Master draws
   it and allows you to use it, but cannot undo the image when done.  You
   must do something to cause the screen to be redrawn by perhaps changing
   layers, or doing a Redraw.  The best answer is to add ram to your
   machine!
@endnode

@node TechSupport "Tech Support for Presentation Master"
If you have problems with Presentation Master, Here is the process for
solving your problem:
 1 Before calling for tech support, try to resolve your problem on your
   own.  Many problems are simply misunderstandings or lack of knowledge
   which can be obtained from the manual, or this help file.  Appendix
   B, Solutions, in the manual may help.  Remember, this help file, and
   the manual, were written by two different people and may provide
   different perspectives on the same subject.  Also, there may be
   different descriptions of an item in different places in either the
   manual or this help file, so look around and see what additional
   insight you gain.
 2 If you utilize bulletin boards, or belong to a user group, there may
   be help either on-line from a BBS or within your user group by locating
   a fellow user of Presentation Master.
 3 Next, if the manual or this help doesn't provide a solution, it may
   be time to contact Oxxi for some tech support.  Be sure you have the
   serial number handy for all correspondence:

   By phone:
     Oxxi Customer Service at 310-427-1227 for first 90 days following
     purchasing and registering your product or if you are outside of
     the U.S.
     Computer Technical Support Services at 1-900-776-6994 if outside of
     the free tech support time stated above.  This is at
     the rate of $1.00 for the first minute and $2.00 for each additional
     minute.
     In each of the above, be prepared to briefly state your problem and
     note the answer or solution the technician gives you.
   By FAX or mail:
     Tech support by FAX or mail is always free.  Be sure to include the
     following information:
             Your program serial number
             Your FAX or phone number
             The description of your problem and how it came up.
             The hardware environment (Amiga model, memory,
                     other boards, etc.).
             The software environment (Kickstart version, Workbench
                     version, other programs running at same time, etc.)
             Peripherals that might be involved (printer, etc.)
     FAX to 310-427-0971
     Mail to:     Oxxi, Inc.
                  Presentation Master Support
                  P.O. Box 90309
                  Long Beach, CA 90808-0309
                  USA
@endnode
